<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Calls For Drug-Free World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan Monday called for joint efforts of
states worldwide to work for a drug-free world.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the Special Session of the
General Assembly on the World Drug Problem, the U.N. chief hoped
the session would be the time for the international community to
find common ground on the establishment of a drug-free world in
the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 world leaders are attending the session that
intends to reduce from 190 million the number of people using
illicit drugs worldwide.
</P>
<P>
"The proposed political declaration is the product of hard work
and effort. It is rare for consensus to be reached on substantive
as well as political issues months in advance of a Special
Session," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The groundbreaking Declaration on the Guiding Principles of
Demand Reduction creates a balanced approach which, for the first
time, addresses the responsibility of nations where consumption is
a problem as well as that of nations where production is a
problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
The declaration on the guilding principles of demand reduction
is intended to help governments set up effective prevention,
treatment and rehabilitation programs.
</P>
<P>
Annan hoped, by the year 2008, that member states will have
made real progress in eliminating or reducing in significant
number the crops of opium poppies, coca and cannabis.
</P>
<P>
"The growing trend in abuse and production of psychotrophic
substance must be reversed," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. International Drug Control Program has risen to the
challenge and shaped a balanced and global strategy to implement
the decisions that will be adopted during the crucial three days,
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The new version represents a quantum leap from the piecemeal
and pilot projects of the past three decades," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
