<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Arrives in Bonn for First Russian-German Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
arrived in Bonn Monday afternoon to attend the first high-level
government consultations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Government ministers including foreign, finance and defense
ministers from both sides will also attend the two-day talks which
are conducted along the lines of regular high-level consultations
Germany holds with some other European countries including France,
Britain and Italy.
</P>
<P>
German officials have said that the consultations, which will
be held once a year in the future, represent a "new quality" of
the German-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also said last week that the upcoming talks would focus
on sketching bilateral relations with Germany until the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Economic issues, such as the recent financial turmoil in
Russia, are expected to be the main topics to be discussed. News
reports said that Yeltsin may use the visit to appeal to Bonn to
back efforts to secure new Western credits to Russia.
</P>
<P>
German government spokesman Otto Hauser, however, dismissed
speculations that bilateral negotiations would be held on new
German financial aid to Russia. Referring to the ongoing
negotiations between Russia and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF), Hauser stressed that Germany would act through multilateral
channels to help Russia.
</P>
<P>
The two sides would also seek coordination on international
issues, especially the Kosovo conflict, officials said. Germany
has stressed that in case of a Western intervention in the Kosovo
conflict, Russia must also be involved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
