<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Orders Inquiry into U.S. Nerve Gas Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen Monday ordered an inquiry into allegations that special U.S.
forces used nerve gas to target American military defectors during
the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
"My understanding is that would, of course, have violated our
own policy at the time," Cohen said in an interview with CNN,
which with the Time magazine issued the report on the use of nerve
gas.
</P>
<P>
"President Nixon had declared an end to use of any kind of
biological weapons," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon was not aware of any information that could back
up those charges, Cohen said. But, he added that he was asking the
military services, including the Air Force and Army, to search
records for any information that might substantiate the
allegations and "to examine it with the kind of seriousness it
warrants."
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that although he was not aware of the matter, "it
doesn't mean that it doesn't exist." He said, "We'll go back and
try to find out as much information as we can."
</P>
<P>
The CNN-Time magazine report said the so-called Operation
Tailwind was approved by the Nixon White House as well as the CIA.
The main source was retired Adm. Thomas Moorer, then chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
The CNN conductor and Time correspondent reported the case
after eight months of investigations.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, former U.S. military officials who
participated in the operation in September 1970 said their job was
to kill defectors from the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
The reported use of nerve gas came after Nixon pledged a "no
first use" policy on nerve gas. The U.S. already had signed a
treaty restricting chemical weapons but the Senate had not
ratified it.
</P>
<P>
Melvin Laird, secretary of defense at the time of Operation
Tailwind, told Time that he had no specific recollection of nerve
gas being used but "I do not dispute what Admiral Moorer has to
say on this matter."
</P>
<P>
Moorer is quoted in the magazine as saying the gas was "by and
large available" for high-risk search-and-rescue missions and that
"this is a much bigger operation than you realize." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
