<HEADLINE> Security Bolstered for Philippines' Independence Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Some 10,000 policemen will be
deployed in some Philippine cities to ensure security during the
celebration of the country's independence from Spain 100 years
ago, a senior police officer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Director-General Santiago Alino, chief of the Philippine
National Police (PNP), said these policemen will be dispatched to
main celebration sites across the country on June 12, the
Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
Alino added that security will be strengthened in Manila,
Malolos and other major cities.
</P>
<P>
Alino said the police authorities have so far received no
report on threats to create trouble during the celebrations. But
he said a blue alert will be declared to keep all Metro Manila
policemen on their toes.
</P>
<P>
Alino said the Presidential Security Group, under Brigade
General Jose Calimlim, would protect the heads of state, very
important personalities and guests attending the celebrations.
</P>
<P>
On reports that militant groups may hold separate rallies on
June 12, Alino said: "We are in a democratic country and rallies
are allowed."
</P>
<P>
Aside from the PNP, the military will also send units to help
maintain peace and order during the centennial affair, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
