<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Pledges to Cut Drug Use by Half in 10 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States aims to
cut American drug use and access by half over the next 10 years,
U.S. President William Clinton said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the anti-drug special session of the United Nations
here Monday morning, the president said that the United States is
committed to defeating drugs and will do its part to make the
anti-drug goal of the world a reality. Year-in and year-out, he
said, the U.S. has provided the largest anti-drug budgets ever in
the country's history.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has long been the largest drug consuming country in
the world.
</P>
<P>
"Americans are spending 37 percent less on drugs today than a
decade ago -- which means 34.1 billion U.S. dollars reinvested in
our society instead of squandered on drugs," he said.
</P>
<P>
America will commit to a five-year, 2 billion U.S. dollar
public-private partnership to teach kids to keep off drugs, he
said. That includes publicity campaigns in forms such as the
exchange of information over the Internet, on the television and
radio and various kinds of researches.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, drug use has dropped 49 percent since
1979. Recent studies show that drug use by American young people
is stabilizing, and in some categories even declining. Over all
cocaine use has dropped 70 percent since 1985. Last year, he
said the U.S. Coast Guard seized more than 100,000 pounds of
cocaine.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president also listed efforts and achievements made by
other nations.
</P>
<P>
"Drugs are every nation's problem," Clinton said. Every nation
must act to fight them. "We must wage this fight around the world
and around the kitchen table," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
