<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Bourse Index Touches 11-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) index plunged to an 11-year low of 311.7 points at midday
Monday before recovering 0.67 points to close at 312.37, a
5.79-point drop from last trading day.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the index had not been so low since 1987 and they
blamed the drop on the regional currency woes and the
deterioration of Japanese and Hong Kong economies.
</P>
<P>
Since June, the Japanese yen has kept falling against the U.S.
dollar and fell through 140 against the greenback on Monday,
showing international investors' lack of confidence in the
country's massive economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the yen fluctuation, the Thai baht was trading
at a 13-week low of 43.8 against the dollar on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The turmoil in the currency market forced the interest rates to
go up, adding fuel to the fall of the stock prices.
</P>
<P>
Bad news was heard all over the Asian region, as Hong Kong and
Malaysia announced contraction of their economic growth in the
first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Bangkok, weekend reports about leading finance
company Phatra Thanakit selling 51 percent of its stake to U.S.
investment bank Merrill Lynch triggered a storm of dumping of
finance companies' stocks.
</P>
<P>
Two large commercial banks, Siam Commercial Bank and Krung Thai
Bank, are likely to increase their capital to 30 billion baht (714
million dollars) and 70 billion baht (1.67 billion dollars)
respectively, inflicting another blow to the already poorly
performing stocks of the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Investors doubted whether the banks have such a strong money
basis.
</P>
<P>
Fears are rising here that the second wave of the Asian
economic crisis could come even more devastatingly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
