<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK to Strip Hereditary Peers of Voting Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Britain's leader of upper house Lord
Ivor Richard said Monday the right of hereditary peers to vote in
the House of Lords would end soon.
</P>
<P>
Lord Richard told the members of the House of Lords that the
government planned to strip the peers of their rights to sit and
vote as part of its wider reform of the upper house.
</P>
<P>
"The continuation of hereditary membership of the second
chamber is not for negotiation," he said in an uncompromising
speech that signaled the end of backstage attempts to negotiate a
compromise with the opposition Conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Richard did not give a timetable but the measure is widely
expected to be announced in October at the start of the next
session of parliament.
</P>
<P>
"In a modern Parliament, there really should be no reserved
seats booked generations ago for a privileged few," he added.
</P>
<P>
Richard said the Lords should remain a revising chamber and
keep its present limited powers, but be composed entirely of
appointed life peers. Unlike their hereditary counterparts, life
peers cannot pass on their titles to their children.
</P>
<P>
Taking away the voting rights of some 750 hereditary peers
would be the biggest change in the role of the second chamber
since 1958, when a Conservative government invented life peers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
