<HEADLINE> Regional Sanitation Disaster Response Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The International Federation of Red
Cross and Red Crescent societies held its first regional training
exercise on water and sanitation disaster response here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 14-day training exercise has been prompted by problems of
mass population movements and the Red Cross' regional capacity to
act quickly and effectively to avert national disasters, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Red Cross Regional Water and Sanitation spokesman Robert
Fraser said that the training exercise is necessary because a lot
of people are being forced into urban settlements where their
health has been affected by poor water and sanitation facilities.
</P>
<P>
Fraser said the strategy of the Red Cross is to encourage the
use of regional human resources. The training exercise is also to
strengthen existing and potential human resources in the southern
African region, he added.
</P>
<P>
"There is need for us to strengthen the Red Cross societies'
capacity to respond to emergencies and provide curative
assistance of safe water and adequate sanitation in the region,"
said Fraser.
</P>
<P>
Water and sanitation interventions have been carried out to
reduce incidences of diseases, improve the quality of life and
reduce the effect to recurrent disasters.
</P>
<P>
The exercise is attended by 25 participants from Angola,
Namibia, Mozambique, Malawi, South Africa, Zambia, Swaziland,
Lesotho and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Funded by Red Cross societies from Britain, Finland, Germany
and Sweden, the exercise will provide a forum for the exchange of
views and experiences and increase national societies' capacity
to identify disaster response teams.
</P>
<P>
A practical exercise on disaster preparedness and responses
will also be part of the whole exercise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
