<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't Orders Pilots to Return to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government ordered
Monday all the striking pilots of Philippine Airlines (PAL) to end
their three-day-old crippling strike and return to work as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Labor Secretary Cresenciano Trajano was quoted by the
Philippine Television as calling on the 620 striking pilots to
report back for work and asking the PAL management to accept these
pilots.
</P>
<P>
But Manolo Aquino, PAL executive vice president, said the PAL
management decided to accept all the striking members of the
Airline Pilots Association of the Philippines (ALPAP) except its
29 leaders.
</P>
<P>
PAL dismissed all the 29 officers of the ALPAP and the other
hundreds of striking union members who refused to abide by a
return-to-work order of PAL Sunday.
</P>
<P>
ALPAP President Sotico Lloren said he has not yet received a
return-to-work order from the labor authorities.
</P>
<P>
Lloren said he will consult his legal counsel about the next
steps the union will take.
</P>
<P>
According to the PAL management, the airline is losing some 150
million pesos (3.8 million U.S. dollars) a day as a result of the
work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
The pilots have been staging the strike in protest of a new
policy by the PAL management to retire pilots who have logged
20,000 flying hours. The pilots condemned the action as unfair and
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
But the PAL management said the policy was already contained in
a collective bargaining agreement signed by the union and the PAL
earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
