<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Astronomers Discover New Star Cluster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. astronomers said Monday in
Los Angeles that they have discovered a mysterious cluster of
newly-formed stars.
</P>
<P>
The cluster of stars, far closer to Earth than expected and
accompanied by a giant "brown dwarf" planet, was discovered by
astronomers from the University of California in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
The astronomers said they were trying to understand how the
cluster was formed and why it had not been discovered sooner.
</P>
<P>
The stars, only 150 light years away from Earth and called "T
Tauri," are normally formed from a huge cloud of molecular gas,
said Benjamin Zuckerman, a professor of physics and astronomy.
</P>
<P>
"Because the newly discovered stars are in our own backyard, a
giant cloud should easily be seen, but there is no sign of it," he
said. "Stars this young shouldn't have traveled far from their
mother cloud. How it could dissipate so quickly is a really
mystery."
</P>
<P>
U.S. scientists said the cluster of stars was about three times
closer to Earth than the newly formed stars normally studied by
astronomers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
