<HEADLINE> 34th OAU Summit Meeting Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 8 (Xinhua) -- African leaders started a
three-day summit meeting Monday morning in an effort to plan
future activities for the promotion of peace and economic
integration in the world's poorest continent.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech at the 34th assembly of heads of state
and government of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
President Blaise Compaore of Burkina Faso expressed deep concern
over the conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Calling for the two countries to settle the crisis through
dialogue and all OAU member states to work for peace in Africa,
the Burkinabe President also stressed the need to boost African
economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Conflict prevention, management and resolution was also the
key point of the address made by OAU Secretary-General Salim
Ahmed Salim at the opening session of the summit, which attracted
more than 30 heads of state and government across Africa.
</P>
<P>
Salim Ahmed Salim said that there could be no chance for
further economic growth unless African countries united to create
a peaceful and stable situation.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela expressed similar views
in a speech to the session.
</P>
<P>
As at previous OAU summits, President of Palestine, Yasser
Arafat was also invited to the gathering.
</P>
<P>
Accusing the stubbon stand of the Isareali government that has
led to a step backward in the peace process, Arafat called for
strong support and assistance from Africa to the just cause and
struggle of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Other key speakers at the opening session include Louise
Frechette, Deputy Secretary-General of the United Nations
orepresenting his chief Kofi Annan, and Robert Mugabe, President
of Zimbabwe and out-going OAU executive chairman.
</P>
<P>
The meeting then elected a 15-member bureau led by Compaore,
the in-coming chairman of the all-Africa organization.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the session, the African leaders left for the
Ouagadougou International Arts Exhibition Center to inaugurate a
week-long exhibition on new information and communication
technologies.
</P>
<P>
The show, jointly organized by OAU and the African Economic
Community, is said to be the first of its kind in Africa aiming
at publicizing the new technologies to the African people.
</P>
</TEXT>
