<HEADLINE> Mexico Calls for Global Strategy for Fighting Illicit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The international community
must undertake an unprecedented cooperation effort, based on a new
strategy that is global, comprehensive and balanced, Mexican
President Emesto Zedillo stressed here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Special Session of the General Assembly of the
United Nations on the World Drug Problem held from June 8 to 9 at
the headquarters of the United Nations, president Zedillo said
drug has become a global problem which demands a global response,
a response assumed by all and shared by all.
</P>
<P>
The president said a global strategy should involve all
countries without exception but also without recrimination, and a
comprehensive one can address all phases of the drug cycle, from
production, sale and trafficking to consumption and its related
crimes.
</P>
<P>
"In this context, efforts to reduce demand must be
significantly strengthened. Demand reduction should be seen as a
public health issue as well as a problem of social behavior and
values, which must be faced with medical, educational, training
and cultural programs," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo said there also should be a balanced strategy in
fighting illicit drugs worldwide with the same rights and
obligations, and with respect for the sovereignty of each nation
so that no one can become the judge of others, and no one feels
entitled to violate other countries' laws for the sake of
enforcing its own.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo said to this end, the United Nations should facilitate
that each country elaborate a plan of action with concrete and
verifiable targets; that each country adhere to the commitments
agreed upon in this meeting; that each country have adequate
legislation against money laundering and the drug related crimes;
and that the United Nations periodically assesses progress in each
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
