<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Cut Foreign Missions for Lack of Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has decided
to cut three of its embassies abroad due to lack of fund, but details
have not been revealed.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all of its foreign missions will be restructured by
downgrading or reducing size, sources in the Foreign Ministry
were quoted by Monday's East African weekly as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report said the measures are aimed at correcting Uganda's
image abroad.
</P>
<P>
The shake-up comes following a financial report which said
Uganda's foreign missions had incurred debts amounting to 4.3
million U.S. Dollars mainly on utilities by June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Some embassy buildings are reported to be in a serious state
of disrepair with leaking roofs, sewage blockage and run-down
furniture and upholstery.
</P>
<P>
Eleven of its 26 foreign missions wrote to parliament in 1997,
complaining about their acute shortage of fund which hampered the
daily operations of the agencies.
</P>
<P>
In a faxed message to parliament, Ugandan Ambassador to
France David Kazungu said, "I have made several appeals to Kampala
but have received no reply. Staff are getting demoralized by the
day as they face eviction."
</P>
<P>
To save the country's face and improve efficiency of foreign
missions, a cabinet meeting decided to close three embassies,
downgrade representative offices to some international
organizations and reduce the diplomatic staff.
</P>
<P>
To help the foreign missions through the hard times, a total
amount of 2.5 million Dollars will be provided to them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
