<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Israeli Peace Activists Back Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian and Israeli peace advocates
Monday expressed their support for the Palestinian people's right
of self-determination and establishing an independent state side
by side with the state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The pre-June 5 borders (before 1967 Middle East War) will be
the basis in establishing permanent borders between the states of
Israel and Palestine, while Jerusalem will finally remain a
unified city," said a joint declaration released by the Egyptian
Peace Movement and Israel's Peace Now movement in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The two movements stressed that Mideast peace should be based
on relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions along with the
land-for-peace formula and the maximum of security for all parties
concerned.
</P>
<P>
The declaration highlighted the need to launch concerted
efforts in the Middle East to rebuild the region and free it from
threats of war, armament race, tension and poverty.
</P>
<P>
"Comprehensive peace should be aimed at rebuilding a region
free from weapons of mass destruction in order to ensure the
mobilization of economic potentials for the prosperity of its
peoples," said the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The two movements addressed an appeal to the peace-loving
forces in Israel, the Arab region and the whole world to support
these principles and pile pressures on the governments concerned
in order to reach peace.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Peace Movement is a group that features a number
of prominent writers and intellectuals. A delegation of Peace Now,
Israel's largest peace group with thousand of members, arrived
here on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The declaration provides a further step towards cooperation
among world peace activists, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
quoted Egyptian peace activist Lotfi el Khouli as saying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first time intellectuals and popular forces
contribute in a public and organized manner to abort the policies
of (Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin) Netanyahu and the radical
forces and open the door to a just, balanced and overall peace,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of this unparalleled document is to "guide
peace on the popular, intellectual and cultural levels to override
the stalemate," he said, adding that "our main affliction is to
change the (Israeli) policies and not the government."
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace process has been gradually grounded to a
standstill since the Likud government taking power two years
ago. International mediation has so far failed to change the
Israeli hard-line policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
