<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Calls for Peace, Development in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 8 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela Monday called on African countries to redouble their
efforts to promote peace and economic development for their
common destiny.
</P>
<P>
As African countries and peoples are bound together with the
common destiny, "none can succeed without the success of the
other," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
The South African President made the remarks at a summit
meeting of the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which opened
Monday morning in the capital of Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
Mandela called for a frank assessment
of the Central Organ for Conflict Prevention, Management and
Resolution Mechanisms set up by OAU.
</P>
<P>
It was particularly so when the "current and most unfortunate
conflict" between Ethiopia and Eritrea has posed a threat to
peace and stability in Africa, he noted.
</P>
<P>
If the central organ is successful, said Mandela, "then we
must seriously address the question of what we need to do to
ensure that the continent truly and collectively takes charge of
its security and stability."
</P>
<P>
In the economic field, Mandela stressed the need to respond
"in practical ways" to the challenge of enhancing cooperation
among African countries.
</P>
<P>
He therefore called for efforts to enhance the effectiveness
of the African Economic Community (AEC) and other sub-regional
economic communities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Africa must, as a matter of emergency, seek closer
relations with important institutions such as the World Bank, the
International Monetary Fund and the World Trade Organization, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Such relations will help African countries to settle the
issues of debts, infrastructural development, capacity building
and greater African participation in the world economy.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the renegotiation of the Lome Convention with
the European Union (EU) is another issue which Africa must handle
"both seriously and with the necessary sense of urgency", Mandela
pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
