<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Rejects No-Confidence Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (parliament)
Monday rejected a no-confidence motion against Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu over the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
The motion, which was presented by the opposition Labor Party,
was defeated by a vote of 38-10 with 1 abstention.
</P>
<P>
Most members of the ruling coalition parties did not take part
in the vote. They complained that the opposition parties have
submitted too many no-confidence motions recently, describing this
as a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
In the past two weeks, three no-confidence motions against the
government were defeated in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks are currently stalemated over
the scope of the further redeployment of Israeli troops in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Labor Knesset whip Elie Goldschmidt noted that Netanyahu
prefers coalition interests to the redeployment, saying Netanyahu
"is making a lot of noise but is not bringing about a redeployment
because he fears for his seat."
</P>
<P>
The right-wing in the ruling Likud coalition has threatened to
topple Netanyahu's government if he hands over more than 9 percent
of the West Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Under Israeli law, at least 61 members of the 120-seat Knesset
must vote in favor of a no-confidence motion for the prime
minister to step down. The coalition parties occupy 61 seats in
the Knesset. 
</P>
</TEXT>
