<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Improve Reproductive Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A five-day regional conference on
improving the quality of reproductive health started Monday here
with emphasis on guidelines and standards for reproductive
health care.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Zimbabwe, Mozambique, Ethiopia, Kenya,
South Africa, Tanzania, Ghana, Uganda among other countries are
attending the meeting to map out strategies on the issue that is now
acknowledged as critical to the existence of the human species,
the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The conference was officially opened by Zimbabwean Deputy
Minister of Health and Child Welfare David Parirenyatwa with a
call to focus on improving the quality of health care in a region
with the highest mortality in the world.
</P>
<P>
"To partly resolve the problem there has been a shift in
health programs in the region from family planning programs which
focus on providing contraception to reproductive health programs
that address the multiple reproductive health development needs,"
said Parirenyatwa.
</P>
<P>
Eddie Mhlanga from the department of health in South Africa
said that it is important to have a correct understanding of
reproductive health which lies at the foundation of human
existence.
</P>
<P>
"There is need for qualitative research if high quality care
is to be addressed," said Mhlanga. 
</P>
