<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Calls for International Solidarity in Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques
Chirac Monday called on the international community to take common
responsibility and show solidarity in its fight against drugs.
</P>
<P>
"The time has come, in the face of this world-girdling menace,
to demonstrate our countries' determination," Chirac said at the
20th Special Session of the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The three-day session opened at U.N. headquarters in New York
early in the day with high-level delegations from some 150
countries being present.
</P>
<P>
"In every corner of the globe, its must be realized that the
United Nations is battle-ready for the fight against drugs," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The French president stressed that the international community
should "counter-attack on every front" of the drug problems,
including the production of illicit substances, the drug trade and
drug profits.
</P>
<P>
He proposed some principles for international anti-drug policy:
</P>
<P>
-- Co-responsibility. Drug elimination cannot be left to a
single category of country, whether it be producer or consumer.
Supply and demand must be reduced simultaneously;
</P>
<P>
-- Solidality. Bilateral and multilateral funding must be
mobilized to help producing countries follow the path of truly
alternative development;
</P>
<P>
-- Firmness. Firmness at home and abroad in the action of the
judiciary, the police and the customs services, while respecting
individual rights. There must be no safe oasis for the syndicates
of crime.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that he expected the U.N. Special Session to give
fresh worldwide impetus to the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
"The spread of this scourge is alarming. An awakening to this
fact is vital. An all-out offensive must be waged," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
