<HEADLINE> Greece Renews Demand for Marbles's Return From London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday expressed its
dissatisfaction with the damage made to the Parthenon marbles and
once again urged London to return it to Athens.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here Monday, Greek Culture Minister
Evangelos Venizelos said that the reports demolished once and for
all the "baseless and provocative" British argument that the
Pathenon marbles were protected and displayed better in London
than in Athens.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the reports in a Sunday British newspaper
that the Parthenon marbles suffered significant and irrevocable
damage about 69 years ago when British Museum staff tried to
restore the marbles to what was mistakenly thought to be their
original color.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed the importance of efforts being made by
the British Committee for the Return of the Friezes, saying that
this reduced even further the number of those who had the temerity
to argue against the return of the Parthenon marbles.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Political Spring party leader Antonis Samaras also
criticized the British government for the damage and called for
the immediate return of the marbles to Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Parthenon marbles, also named Elgin marbles, were removed
from the Parthenon temple in Athens and transported to London in
1803 by British diplomat Lord Elgin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
