<HEADLINE> U.S. Criticizes Belarus Eviction of Foreign Missions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. ambassador to Belarus on
Monday criticized Minsk for its decision to evict diplomatic
missions from the Drozdy governmental compound, saying the move
could undermine its international image.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Daniel Speckhard told a press conference in Minsk
that the eviction of diplomatic missions from their premises
against their will constitutes a violation of the Vienna
Convention, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
About 20 diplomatic missions were housed in the Drozdy
compound. The Belarus authorities notified the missions in early
May that work would soon be started to overhaul the compound's
water and sewage systems, which were last repaired about 40 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
The missions were advised to vacate their premises by next
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speckhard warned that the Belarussian decision might affect
bilateral economic cooperation, saying Minsk could do the repair
work without evicting the diplomatic missions.
</P>
<P>
However, he said Washington would not take retaliatory actions
against the Belarus mission in Washington, although the Vienna
Convention provides such a possibility.
</P>
<P>
Speckhard said the U.S. diplomatic staff are concerned not just
about moving but about the absence of any guarantees that they
will be able to return to their premises after the repairs.
</P>
<P>
The Belarus Foreign Ministry said it proposed that employees of
the diplomatic missions either move to new buildings in central
Minsk and the Krylovo governmental compound, or begin construction
of their own buildings near Minsk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
