<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Americans Reading News on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The percentage of Americans
getting news from the Internet at least once a week more than
tripled in the past two years -- going from 11 million to 36
million news users.
</P>
<P>
Most people use the Internet to supplement, not replace, their
traditional sources of news, according to a new study by Pew
Research Center, an independent opinion research group that
studies attitudes toward press, politics and public policy issues.
</P>
<P>
For those who go online, science, health, finance and
technology are big news draws, said the survey of 3,002 adults.
</P>
<P>
Despite dramatic growth in online news consumption, cable
television's impact remains far greater. Fully 40 percent of
Americans now regularly watch one of the cable news networks,
whose advantage lies in its immediacy. Americans say that they
would turn to cable channels first in the event of a big news
story, whether it concerned politics, health or sports.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that 46 percent of Americans only follow
national news when something major is happening, and 63 percent of
the people react the same to international news. Only local news
attracts a large regular audience that is not event driven -- 61
percent of Americans follow it most of the time.
</P>
<P>
While accuracy and timeliness are the news values most
important to consumers, the study found that a large segment of
the news audience wants entertaining and enjoyable news presented
by personalities who deliver it in a caring way.
</P>
<P>
Illustrating how differently the generations are responding to
the information explosion, the polling found that only 33 percent
of Americans ages 18-29 keep up with the news a lot, but 77
percent like having so many information sources. In contrast, 68
percent of seniors like following in the news, but only 52 percent
like all the television news shows, magazines and computer
information services at their disposal today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-08 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Following are economic briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Abu Dhabi National Co. for Oil declared
Sunday the creation of the first petrochemical firm which is
wholly owned by itself without any foreign participation.
</P>
<P>
The company also said it signed a contract with the joint
venture of "Taknib Pactel" on the implementation of the
engineering works of the second phase of the project for on-shore
gas development.
</P>
<P>
The production capacity of the project will be 280 million
cubic meters of ready-to-use gas per day.
</P>
<P>
The capital of the petrochemical firm and the gas project
exceeds 2 billion U.S. dollars. They are part of the plan being
carried out by the United Arab Emirates for developing the
petrochemical and gas industries with the participation of foreign
firms and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syrian Oil Minister Maher Hosni Jamal said
at the inauguration ceremony of the first international oil and
gas fair on Sunday that Syria had recently signed four contracts
with foreign firms on oil prospection.
</P>
<P>
Syria is still holding negotiations with two Canadian and Dutch
firms on oil prospection deals, the Syrian minister added.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syria has signed with Erixon, of Sweden, a contract
on investing 118 million U.S. dollars in installing 1 million new
telephone lines, the Arabic El-Hayat daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is part of the project for installing 1.65
million lines in Syria, will feed the increasing demand for
communication services in urban and rural areas alike. The number
of telephone lines in Syria will be increased from 6.5 to 14 lines
per hundred persons.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, 1.65 million lines as well as three digital
networks for connecting the cities around the country and
expanding the existing international network would be installed.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's Minister of Agriculture Mijhim Kreishah is
expected to pay a visit to Israel soon to remove obstacles placed
by Israel on exporting Jordanian commodities to the
Palestinian-controlled areas, Jordan's official news agency Petra
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Khreisha's mission is in line with the agreement which Jordan
and Israel reached last March when Jordan's Crown Prince
Hassan paid an official visit to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been trying to maintain its monopoly over the
Palestinian markets, which absorb 2.7 billion to 4 billion
U.S. dollars worth of Israeli-made products per year, or 95
percent of the annual Palestinian imports. Due to Israel's tight
control, Jordan faces difficulties in exporting its products to
the Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Mukhtar Khattab, advisor to Egyptian Public Enterprise
Sector Minister Ateb Mohamed Ebeid, said Sunday that 105 of 314
state-owned companies had been sold under Egypt's privatization
program.
</P>
<P>
According to Khattab, these companies were sold at 8.4 billion
Egyptian pounds (2.48 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
One third of the income was allocated for the implementation
of the early retirement program at these companies as well as
reimbursement of debts due to banks. The other two thirds were
allocated for repaying national debt, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the privatization program includes selling 10
companies every three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
