<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Asks for Better Oversight in Human Medical Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Government is asking
for better oversight of human medical tests, finding inadequate
current protections for the hundreds of thousands of people
participating in such research each year, USA Today reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The long-established system for protecting human research
subjects has vulnerabilities that threaten its effectiveness,"
according to reports to be issued this week by the Department of
Health and Human Services (HHS), the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The reports "do not claim widespread abuses of human research
subjects." But they "do provide a warning signal of a system that
is in jeopardy" to such a degree that it is now "a serious
national issue."
</P>
<P>
The HHS reports will be presented to a subcommittee of the
Government Reform and Oversight Committee of the House of
Representatives later this week.
</P>
<P>
Contributing to the problem is the speed of medical research
and drug companies' race to create new products, according to the
reports.
</P>
<P>
Among the concerns are:
</P>
<P>
The number and size of various trials have grown
astronomically, creating a "pressure-cooker atmosphere;"
</P>
<P>
Ethics boards that supervise such trials "review too much, too
quickly;"
</P>
<P>
Competition for research money "can compromise human-subject
protections;"
</P>
<P>
Volunteers don't understand that they are test subjects first,
patients second. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
