<HEADLINE> E. African Military Chiefs to Review Joint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Chiefs of general staff from
Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda are expected in Lodwar, northern Kenya
from June 16 as their forces enter the final stage of a joint
training exercise, Kenyan Defense Ministry told Xinhua Monday.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, which involves about 2,000 soldiers from the
three east African countries and 120 U.S. army trainers, started
on June 2 and will end on June 27, said the ministry's spokesman
George Nyakundi.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, code-named Natural Fire'98, is aimed at exposing
the soldiers to future involvement in multinational peacekeeping
operations under the United Nations, said Nyakundi.
</P>
<P>
The troops are at the Moi Barracks in Eldoret of western Kenya
and will proceed to northern Turkana District next week for
another two weeks of field training.
</P>
<P>
The defense spokesman said that training focuses on dealing
with a hypothetical state called Somanga, which is troubled and
the forces work to restore order within the perimeters of the
U.N. peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued last week in Eldoret, Kenyan Brigadier
J.M. Kilela said that the move is a landmark in the history of
the region as it is the first ever military exercise to be
undertaken jointly by the defense forces by the three countries.
</P>
<P>
This pre-deployment training is being conducted under the
auspices of the East African Cooperation (EAC), Kilela said,
noting it is a step forward in furthering regional military
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
