<HEADLINE> UK Railway Workers to Strike 11 Days Nationwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of British railway
maintenance workers Monday called two national strikes expected to
last a total of 11 days in a dispute over pay and working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The action would cause "significant disruption" to national
rail services, said the Rail, Maritime and Transport Union (RMT).
</P>
<P>
The staff who look after track, signaling and power supplies
plan to stop work from June 19 until June 23 and then again from
June 29 until July 5.
</P>
<P>
The RMT called the strike in a bid to get more pay and fewer
working hours for employees of Railtrack Plc, which operates the
national railway network.
</P>
<P>
RMT chief Jimmy Knapp said engineering firms had asked for too
much in return for too little compensation under plans to
restructure pay and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
"This is a dispute about fairness.... We are dealing with an
industry where Railtrack announced profits of 388 million pounds
(632.9 million U.S. dollars) last week and where the collective
profit from the maintenance companies is 300 million pounds a
year," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
