<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda To Retrench 10,000 Civil Servants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's restructuring of
government ministries will lead to laying off of some 10,000
civil servants in the coming financial year.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi-based East African weekly reported Monday that the
workers to be axed include those who have reached their
retirement age or whose contracts have expired, and those without
adequate academic qualifications and poor performers will also be
on the list.
</P>
<P>
Among the ministries affected are education and sports, local
government, labor and social welfare as well as that of
information which is already defunct. The former planning and
economic development ministry, re-merged with finance in May, and
that of tourism, wildlife and antiquities, are also affected.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education has indicated that it will
retrench at least 6,000 teachers, mostly those recruited for the
universal primary education program.
</P>
<P>
A substantial amount of money is reported to have been
earmarked in the forthcoming budget for the terminal benefits to
the targeted workers.
</P>
<P>
When explaining the overhaul in a May 25 circular, Florence
Mugasha who is in charge of civil service in the President's
Office said that the retrenchment mainly targets administrative
staff, with some ministries set to lose more than half of their
present work force.
</P>
<P>
A number of ministries will share office premises to cut down
on rent, the circular said. Most ministries have been spending
a quarter of their budget on office rent.
</P>
<P>
By July 1997, Uganda's civil service had been reduced to about
180,000 people, down from 320,000 before the government embarked
in a vigorous adjustment program between 1990 and 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
