<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Abacha Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's former head of state, Sani
Abacha died in his sleep in the early hour of Monday, in Nigerian
capital Abuja, the official News Agency of Nigeria said, quoting
a statement from the Chief of Defense Staff Abdulsalam Abubakar
made Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed report said Abubakar has resumed leadership of the
west African country.
</P>
<P>
The statement from the chief of staff said Abacha will be
buried later Monday in his hometown in Kano, in northern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Before the announcement of the death, the provisional ruling
council, the country's highest decision-making body, met in Abuja
to review the situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to continue at 11:00 p.m. Monday
evening, after the burial ceremony, the Nigerian News Agency
said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the mood at the State House was that of shock as
most aides and other staff gathered in groups discussing the
development.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, born on Septeber 20, 1943, took over power in November
1993.
</P>
<P>
According to the transition to civil rule program announced in
1995, Abacha is expected to handover power to an elected civilian
government in October this year.
</P>
<P>
In April, five political parties in Nigeria adopted Abacha as
their consensus candidate for the presidential election scheduled
for August 1. but Abacha has been silent on the issue until his
death.
</P>
<P>
Abacha has been reportedly suffering from serious liver
diseases for a long time. Some western diplomats in Lagos said he
died of heart attack. 
</P>
