<HEADLINE> Iraq, Jordan Agree to Enhance Health Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Jordan on Monday signed
minutes on enhancing cooperation in health, pharmaceutical and medical
prevention fields, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The minutes were signed by Iraqi Health Minister Umaid Midhat
Mubarak and his Jordanian counterpart Ashraf Al-Kurdi at the end
of their two-day talks.
</P>
<P>
Under the minutes, the two countries are to launch an
Jordanian-Iraqi Medical Week in Jordanian capital Amman in the
coming few days.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to exchange medical expertise between their
hospitals in a way to improve the medical services in both
countries. Moreover, activities of joint medical committees and
means of upgrading their future talks will be followed up.
</P>
<P>
Al-Kurdi arrived here last Friday, leading a 100-plus medical
delegation to participate in the Iraqi-Jordanian Medical Week held
here Sunday. He met with by Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadhan on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During its stay here, a Jordanian medical team included in
the delegation performed a number of surgeries in Iraqi hospitals.
</P>
<P>
In their talks, the two sides focused discussions on ways of
boosting bilateral health cooperation with an aim of helping Iraq
cope with the worsening health situation due to the long years of
U.N. sanctions imposed in 1990 following Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said that hundreds of thousands of its people, mostly
children, have died as a result of the sanctions-caused shortage of
food and medical supplies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
