<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Allows Bank Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has for the first time allowed
the sale of state-owned banks.
</P>
<P>
However, Egyptian officials stressed that the bank
privatization is not the work of pressure of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian People's Assembly (parliament) Monday approved in
principle a bill regulating contribution of the private sector in
the capital of public sector banks, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The bill says that the private sector may contribute in the
shares of the capital of banks wholly-owned by the state, MENA
said, without saying when the government will offer the banks for
sale.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the parliamentary Economic Committee Abdulla Tayel
said the private sector may not own more than 10 percent of the
shares of state-owned banks.
</P>
<P>
"It may hold a higher share temporarily and this should be
rectified in two years," he said.
</P>
<P>
The committee presented the bill in May to privatize the four
national banks, which include the National bank of Egypt, Misr
Bank, Bank of Alexandria and National Investment Bank.
</P>
<P>
The four banks now hold 70 percent of the country's commercial
assets. The share will be brought down to 60 percent before the
end of the year, although actual privatization would be later.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on debates on the bill, Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri said that Egypt's decision is "independent" and
imposed by "nobody in the world, a state or a financial
institution."
</P>
<P>
The letter of intent in 1993 in which the Egyptian government
says it will sell banks by the year 1995 has been canceled. The
two sides signed another letter of intent in November 1996
outlining the country's economic policy.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Economy Yousef Boutros Ghali Sunday
categorically denied that Egypt's privatization of its banking
sector was a response to IMF pressures.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that Egypt "might seek some foreign
experience to develop the banking sector. But Egyptians will be
responsible in the first place for developing this important
sector."
</P>
<P>
The move to privatize the banks and state-held insurance
companies has unleashed a wave of protests in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Opponents of the privatization scheme warned that selling
national banks would undermine the national economy.
</P>
<P>
But Boutros Ghali told reporters earlier that privatization
would be accompanied by strict government measures to protect
depositors, including Central Bank intervention in case of
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian, Eritrean Catholic Bishops Appeal for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Catholic bishops of Ethiopia
and Eritrea Monday appealed to the Ethiopian and Eritrean
governments to settle their present conflict peacefully and
expeditiously, thus eliminating any danger of war.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here after an extraordinary session, the
bishops noted that they have been deeply saddened by reports of
tensions and the news of armed conflicts between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
They said that the tragic consequences of these tensions may
lead to an all-out war among brothers who share a
common history and tradition.
</P>
<P>
The bishops pointed out that after 30 years of devastating war
and only seven years of peace, recent reports of an armed
conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea have come as a complete
surprise to the world and, above all, to the peoples of both
countries who were beginning to forget the scars of their history
and were fully engaged in building up the economic structures of
their countries.
</P>
<P>
Not only do the present tensions put this economic development
in jeopardy, but an eventual escalation of war will destabilize
the already delicate political balance in the Horn of Africa, the
bishops stressed. 
</P>
