<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Abacha and His Leadership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's military leader General
Sani Abacha died a sudden death in his sleep in the early hour of
Monday, two month before the presidential election in which he is
the sole candidate.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the long-time rumor that he was suffering serious
liver disease, unconfirmed report said that he died of an heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
Born on September 20, 1943, in Kano State in northern Nigeria,
Abacha went through all the ranks of the armed forces until he
was promoted to a general in October 1990.
</P>
<P>
Abacha was appointed the defense minister in August 1990 by
the then government of General Ibrahim Babangida.
</P>
<P>
He took over power on November 17, 1993 from the interim
government of Earnest Shonekan, a product of the crisis caused by
the annulment of the June 12, 1993 presidential election by the
Babangida government.
</P>
<P>
Chief M.K. Abiola was widely believed to be the winner of that
election, but he was put into jail later by the Abacha government
when he announced himself President of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Abiola's supporters have been demanding his
release, and if possible, the recognition of his winnership.
</P>
<P>
For the annulment of the 1993 election and the execution of
the Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other Ogoni minority activists on
charges of murder, Abacha's government has been sanctioned by the
West which criticized him for dictatorship and violation of human
rights.
</P>
<P>
In his less than five years of leadership, Abacha has survived
two coup plots, one in March 1995, in which former head of state,
General Olusegun Obasanjo and 40 others were arrested.
</P>
<P>
The other was in December 1997, which saw the fall of the
number two leader, Chief of General Staff Lieutenant-General
Oladipo Diya.
</P>
<P>
In October 1995, Abacha announced a three-year transition to
civil rule program, in which he promised to hand over power to an
elected civilian government in October this year.
</P>
<P>
In April, Nigeria's five political parties adopted Abacha as
their sole consensus candidate for the presidential election
scheduled on August 1, which was seen by some pro-democracy
groups as another evidence of Abacha's rigging of the transition
program.
</P>
<P>
Though Abacha has been silent on his candidacy until his
death, the pro-democracy groups said that Abacha is certain to
succeed himself in October.
</P>
<P>
Though he was never spared by the West for alleged
dictatorship and bad records of human rights, there were always
praises for what he has done for Nigeria and the whole sub-region
of west Africa.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, under the leadership of Abacha, has seen solid
achievements in stabilizing its economy. The inflation rate went
down from several hundred percent when he took the leadership to
the current seven percent.
</P>
<P>
The value of the Nigerian currency Naira has been stabilized,
and the country's foreign reserve has been increasing steadily in
the last two years.
</P>
<P>
The whole economy is on the way of recovery, with a growth
rate of about 3.7 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Abacha recorded an even greater success in maintaining peace
in the west African sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria had since 1990 contributed great political leadership
as well as human and financial resources to the west African
peacekeeping force in Liberia known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
It was due to ECOMOG's efforts that the Liberian civil war was
finally brought to an end in August 1997, with the establishment
of the Charles Taylor government through a peaceful election.
</P>
<P>
It was also due to Nigeria's leadership that ECOMOG intervened
immediately after the coup in neighboring Sierra Leone last May.
Elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah were eventually reinstated
in March with the help of ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
Abacha's contribution to regional peace and stability was
recognized Monday at the Organization of African Unity summit now
going on in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso, when the leaders observed
a silence for him.
</P>
<P>
With just two months to the presidential election now without
any candidate, the fate of Nigeria is now indeed at stake.
</P>
<P>
As the military force is now consulting over who is to lead
the most populous nation in Africa, it is not known whether they
will allow the transition program to continue on its course or
anything else.
</P>
<P>
In most of its time since independence in October 1967,
Nigeria has been ruled by successive military governments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
