<HEADLINE> U.S. Threatens Retaliation Against Belarus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States threatened on
Monday to retaliate against Belarus if the Belarussian authorities
persist in attempts to vacate the U.S. ambassador's residence in
Minsk.
</P>
<P>
"We have urged the government to halt this self-destructive
action and if the government in Belarus makes it impossible for
our ambassador to carry out his responsibilities, we will be
forced to take retaliatory action," said State Department
spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
The Belarussian government indicated that all residences in the
neighborhood area, where the U.S. ambassador's residence is
located, should be vacated by Wednesday, June 10th, to allow the
government to replace utility lines in the area.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, workers from the Belarussian government
welded shut a side gate leading to the residence of the U.S.
ambassador, Daniel Speckard.
</P>
<P>
But the front gate to the residence is still open, though
indications are that road access to the area will be blocked in a
few days, and the ambassador is still in the residence, said Rubin
</P>
<P>
"We and the dozen other countries facing eviction have made
clear that this action by the government of Belarus is a violation
of the Vienna Convention on diplomatic relations. The residence
of an ambassador is inviolable," noted Rubin.
</P>
<P>
"The host government is obligated under the convention to take
all appropriate steps to protect the residence and to make sure
that it is supplied with adequate services," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
He argued that the Belarussian government's action is also
inconsistent with the lease contract, which will remain valid until
2001.
</P>
<P>
When asked what retaliatory action could be taken, Rubin
replied, "We certainly would have options of our own in the
welding area here in Washington."  
</P>
</TEXT>
