<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Joins Others in Calling for Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Tuesday joined
seven other countries in issuing a declaration calling for
immediate steps to be taken toward international nuclear
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was also signed by Ireland, Sweden, New
Zealand, Egypt, Brazil, Mexico and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
The declaration, announced by South African Deputy Foreign
Minister Aziz Pahad in Cape Town and also by foreign ministers in
various capitals simultaneously, said the possession of nuclear
weapons poses continued threat to humanity and the recent nuclear
tests by India and Pakistan underscored the predicament.
</P>
<P>
The world could no longer remain complacent at the reluctance
of states which possessed or had the capacity to produce nuclear
weapons to take fundamental steps toward the speedy and total
elimination of these weapons, Pahad said.
</P>
<P>
The declaration called on the five recognized nuclear states,
as well as the three capable of manufacturing nuclear weapons --
India, Pakistan and Israel -- to make this commitment and take
immediate practical steps.
</P>
<P>
For the process to start, India, Pakistan and Israel should
clearly and urgently reverse the pursuit of their respective
nuclear weapons development or deployment plans, and refrain from
any actions that could undermine the international community's
efforts toward nuclear disarmament, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The elimination of nuclear arsenals and the development of
requisite verification regimes would require time, but there were
a number of practical steps that these states could and should
take immediately, it said.
</P>
<P>
The declaration called on the three states, and all other
states who had not yet done so, to adhere to the
non-proliferation treaty and to take the necessary measures
flowing from this adherence.
</P>
<P>
"We likewise call on them to sign and ratify the Comprehensive
Nuclear Test Ban Treaty without delay and without conditions,"
the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The permanent representatives of Ireland, South Africa, New
Zealand and Sweden at the United Nations will seek a meeting with
the UN Secretary-General Tuesday to hand over the declaration and
to request its issue as a document of the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
