<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Spring Warmest in 50 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada's spring this year was the
warmest ever officially recorded in the country, reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The average temperature in Canada over the past three months
was more than 3.1 degrees centigrade above normal, making it the
warmest spring the country has experienced since 1948.
</P>
<P>
Canada began to record temperature nationwide 50 years ago when
a network of weather stations was established.
</P>
<P>
The warm spring follows a mild winter as Canada experienced the
effects of a strong El Nino, which is now weakening in the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, the warm spring has been marked by reduced rainfall
and an increased number of forest fires, especially in Alberta and
Ontario provinces.
</P>
<P>
In other parts of the world, this spring was also warmer than
usual. The average global temperature is reported to rise by more
than half a degree in the first five months over the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Vice President Al Gore said on Monday that the past five
months were the warmest in earth's modern history.
</P>
<P>
"This is a reminder once again that global warming is real and
that unless we act we can expect more extreme weather in the years
ahead," Gore said.
</P>
<P>
Most scientists believe that the earth's atmosphere is slowly
being warmed as man-made greenhouse gases absorb heat that would
otherwise escape into outer space. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Oil Minister Visits Kuwait on Oil Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Minister of Petroleum Ali
Al-Naimi arrived here Tuesday for a visit aimed at seeking support
for an effort to stabilize the world oil market and raise oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi minister is scheduled to hold talks with his Kuwaiti
counterpart Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah on matters concerning the
tough situation on the international oil markets, Kuwaiti official
news agency Kuna reported.
</P>
<P>
Al-Naimi's visit is believed to be part of a Gulf tour
designed to rally support for a recent tripartite agreement
involving Riyadh to slash oil output, according to Kuna.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, Mexico and Venezuela agreed last Thursday in
Amsterdam, the Netherlands, to reduce their oil production by
450,000 barrels per day from July 1, a strategy aimed at boosting
oil prices which have dropped to low levels between 12 and 14
U.S. dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Al-Naimi disclosed Sunday, after a tour to Oman, the United
Arab Emirates and Qatar, that these three countries are ready to
effectively contribute to stabilizing the global oil markets.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, responding positively to the tripartite oil reduction
agreement, said it supports any measure to prompt a rally of oil
prices, but declined to say what action it will take in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of the oil ministers of the Gulf Cooperation Council
is scheduled to be held in Riyadh on June 16. World oil producers
reached a deal in Saudi Arabia last March to reduce output by 1.5
million barrels per day in a bid to shore up prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
