<HEADLINE> Ramos Urges Big Banks to Acquire Cash-Strapped Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
Tuesday urged big banking institutions to consider acquiring
smaller cash-strapped banks following the closure of another
thrift bank because of insolvency.
</P>
<P>
"We have to see more of the merging or the acquisition by the
bigger banks of the smaller banks which are in difficulties,"
Ramos said in a press briefing in Kawit town, Cavite province.
</P>
<P>
Ramos was reacting to the recent closure order slapped by the
central bank on Commonwealth Savings and Loans Bank.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank is the third thrift bank to be put under the
receivership of the Philippine Deposit Insurance Corp. since the
Asian financial storm hit the country in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' call is in line with the central bank's earlier
statement encouraging bigger banks to consider resolving the
difficulties of needy smaller ones by either merging with them or
acquiring them.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said in an earlier
interview that this development is not expected to shake
confidence in the country's banking system as Commonwealth Bank is
just a small bank.
</P>
<P>
"This is no cause for (concern). It's a very, very small bank.
Besides, probably most of those depositors are insured
depositors," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
