<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Airline Profits Hit by Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Asian economic crisis is
expected to drag down world airline profits by 1.1 billion
U.S. dollars this year, the International Air Transport
Association (IATA) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Airline profits will likely slip to 3.9 billion dollars as
opposed to last year's 5 billion on combined revenues of the
agency's 258-member airlines of 145.7 billion, the Montreal-based
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Global air traffic will grow by 5 percent this year, and the
combined revenues will increase by 2.6 percent to 151.5 billion
dollars, it said.
</P>
<P>
The drop in profit was blamed on an expected faster-than-demand
rise of 6 percent in capacity amid the Asian economic crisis,
said IATA Director-General Pierre Jeanniot.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian carriers' 1997 financial performance was,
collectively, probably their worst ever," Jeanniot said, referring
to the economic crisis ripping through Southeast Asia for almost
one year.
</P>
<P>
The Asian airlines will have to move quickly to remove older
aircraft and other inefficiencies hidden by years of strong
growth, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In another big challenge, Jeanniot said airlines will have to
spend about 1.6 billion dollars to solve the millennium year 2000
computer problem.
</P>
<P>
Jeanniot said his agency has undertaken a project to ensure
that the world's airports are ready. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report Urges State Enterprises to Use More Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A report issued today recommends
that China encourage money-losing state-owned enterprises to
draw more investment from overseas to make them profitable.
</P>
<P>
The report was written by the prestigious Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences and based on a survey of 180 foreign-invested
state firms in eight big cities, including Beijing, Shanghai and
Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
Foreign money has been a major factor in renovating state-owned
firms and helping them establish a modern enterprise system, the
report states. "The country should further liberate its minds to
woo foreign investors," it adds.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 percent of overseas-invested projects in Chinese cities
have involved state-owned enterprises, and thousands of state
firms have used foreign money in the 1990s, the report states.
</P>
<P>
The products are better and the efficiency is higher in
foreign-invested firms, which is a result of advanced management
and technology brought by industrialized countries and regions,
the report notes.
</P>
<P>
The report urges that irrational restrictions on attracting
foreign capital be lifted. "If the productivity can be improved,
people's living standards increased, and the country's
comprehensive strength enhanced, no restrictions should be imposed
in this respect," the report states.
</P>
<P>
Two policies should be avoided, according to the report: one is
to let foreign money enter the Chinese market freely; and the
other is to build a shield to block foreign investors in the name
of protecting the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the report suggests that channels to attract foreign
investment be widened, and the country should allow companies from
overseas to buy or merge middle- and small-size state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
However, the state should continue to control key industries
that are vital to the nation, the report states.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, Japan and the United States are the top three
investors in Chinese state enterprises, the report states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
