<HEADLINE> Torrential Rains Hit Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Torrential rains lashed Hong Kong
on Tuesday, forcing schools and some government and commercial
services to close.
</P>
<P>
Authorities sent out the first black rainstorm warning this
year at 6:35 a.m. local time, meaning that heavy rain had fallen
or was expected to fall and that people should stay at secure
places.
</P>
<P>
Some three hours later the signal was lowered to a less severe
red warning, which lasted till 9:00 p.m. Also in force was a
landslip warning, with the authorities advising people living
around Hong Kong's steep hillsides to be alert.
</P>
<P>
All schools, including evening schools, were closed in the day
while courts, clinics and the stock exchange were shut in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
Air traffic was slightly affected with four arrivals and six
departures delayed as up to 10:00 a.m., the Civil Aviation
Department said.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 millimeters of rainfall was recorded across Hong
Kong during the day. In some places of the New Territories and
Kowloon, more than 300 millimeters of rainfall was recorded,
making the day the most rainy day ever seen in June, according to
the Hong Kong Observatory.
</P>
<P>
TV pictures showed that police dispatched a boat to rescue
trapped village people in the northern New Territories.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 cases of landslide and flooding have been
reported since early morning.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
