<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Urges Pilots to Return to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos on Tuesday
called on the hundreds of striking pilots of Philippine Airlines
(PAL) to return to work and end their four-day-old crippling
strike.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held in Kawit town, Cavite province near
Manila, Ramos said the 620-strong pilots union of PAL must comply
with the return-to-work order issued by the Department of Labor
and Employment.
</P>
<P>
Ramos deplored the hardened stances taken by both the striking
pilots and PAL management to the detriment of the riding public
and the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The strike has disrupted flight operations of PAL, stranding
thousands of Filipinos and foreign visitors attending the
celebrations of the Philippines' 100th anniversary of independence
from Spain on June 12.
</P>
<P>
Both the striking union and PAL management hardened their
stances, refusing any compromise despite the mediation of the
Department of Labor and Employment.
</P>
<P>
The Airlines Pilots Association of the Philippines (ALPAP) has
protested PAL's decision to retire pilots who have logged 20,000
hours of flying regardless of age in accordance with a collective
bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
ALPAP said this is unfair because they are deprived of their
security of tenure. But the PAL management said the retirement
policy was already agreed by the ALPAP itself.
</P>
<P>
Labor Secretary Cresencio Trajano issued a return-to-work order
Monday to all PAL strikers who however have refused to heed the
directive.
</P>
<P>
The pilots vowed to continue their strike "to the bitter end."
</P>
<P>
PAL said the strike has cost the company some 150 million to
200 million pesos (5.1 million U.S. dollars) of losses a day.
</P>
<P>
The strike has crippled PAL with only 20 percent of its planes
operating, flown by pilots who are top officials of PAL.
</P>
<P>
Since the pilots ignored the return-to-work order, PAL
retaliated by firing all the striking ALPAP members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
