<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece to Ask UNESCO to Inspect Damaged Parthenon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Greece would ask the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) or the
body's International Council of Museums to set up a committee to
inspect the condition of the Parthenon Marbles damaged by Britain,
a Greek government official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Greek Culture Minister
Evangelos Venizelos praised British historian William St. Clair
for his courage to bring to light the event.
</P>
<P>
St. Clair said in a book released Sunday that the Parthenon
marbles had suffered significant and irrevocable damage some 60
years ago when British Museum staff tried to restore the friezes
to what was mistakenly thought to be their original color.
</P>
<P>
The marbles, 17 figures and part of a frieze more than 160
yards long, have been housed in the British Museum in London since
the early 19th century, when Lord Elgin, then Britain's ambassador
to the Ottoman Empire, removed them from Athens' ancient Parthenon
Temple atop the Acropolis.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Greece has been strongly demanding the return
of the marbles from London to Athens, but this has never been met
by Britain who has long said that the marbles are protected and
displayed better in London than in Athens.
</P>
<P>
Venizelos stressed that the campaign for the return of the
marbles was Greece's duty, to whom the marbles belong.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that he would send a letter Tuesday to his
British counterpart Chris Smith renewing Athens' call for the
return of the marbles.
</P>
<P>
Although he did not reveal the contents of the letter, sources
said that one of Greece's proposals for the return of the marbles
would involve a permanent cooperation on exhibitions between the
British Museum and Greek Museums. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0100 </DOCNO>
