<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADF Nominates Bangladesh P.M. for Nobel Peace Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina has been nominated by the South Asia Democracy Forum (SADF)
for Nobel Peace Prize for the year 1998 for her contribution to
the cause of peace, the Dhaka-based South Asian News Agency said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The SADF, recognizing Hasina's peace initiatives in the
Chittagong Hill Tracts, more than 200 kilometers southeast of
here, made the nomination recently by a jury of eminent
personalities from the seven member states of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), the independent news
agency stated.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation has been conveyed to the Nobel Foundation in
Oslo for consideration, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Hasina has set an example of restoring peace in southeastern
Bangladesh by signing the historic peace agreement with tribal
rebels in December 1997, the SADF was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"With Hasina going ahead with the peace agreement with tribal
rebels, the concept of peaceful existence has found its roots
among different ethnic groups in Bangladesh," the SADF said.
</P>
<P>
The peace agreement ended strife in the three hill districts of
Khagrachhari, Bandarban and Rangamati that left about 22,000
civilians dead during two decades of guerrilla warfare, the SADF
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The SADF is based in Dhaka, with branches in India, Pakistan,
Sri Lanka, Nepal, Bhutan and the Maldives, which together with
Bangladesh are all SAARC members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
