<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Boat People Returned to Hanoi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A group of 154 Vietnamese,
including 153 illegal immigrants and one migrant, were returned by
air to Hanoi, Vietnam, on Tuesday, the Hong Kong government
announced.
</P>
<P>
It was the 121st flight under the Orderly Repatriation Program
(ORP) and the group brought to 12,758 the total number repatriated
on ORP flights since October 1991.
</P>
<P>
The returnees comprised 141 men and 13 women. The majority of
them arrived in Hong Kong in 1998, with the remaining in 1988,
1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong closed the last detention center, the High Island
Detention Center, for Vietnamese people just two weeks ago, which
was hailed by a senior Security Bureau official as "a landmark
achievement in the final chapter of the whole Vietnamese boat
people saga."
</P>
<P>
The problem emerged in 1975 and has since then daunted the
densely populated city. When things were at their worst in October
1991, Hong Kong had to accommodate more than 64,300 Vietnamese
people in 14 camps.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has made vigorous efforts to solve the problem. Some
143,500 Vietnamese refugees have been resettled overseas and about
70,000 Vietnamese migrants and illegal immigrants have been
repatriated to their native country. Now the Vietnamese population
in Hong Kong has dropped to some 2,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
