<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Raise $5.3M Through Privatization in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government is seeking
to raise about 5.3 million U.S. Dollars for the 1998 fiscal year
through its three-year privatization program, Rwanda News Agency
(RNA) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government will raise the money for its 1998 budget
through divesting, liquidating and hiring out of state-owned
enterprises under the three-year privatization program of public
sector.
</P>
<P>
RNA quoted Director of Privatization in the Ministry of
Finance and Economic Planning, Vianney Shumbusho, as saying that
"from 1998 to 2001 government expects to have privatized about 44
public enterprises, sold its shares in six companies and about
five enterprises to have been liquidated."
</P>
<P>
Up to May 29, the Rwandan government earned about three
million U.S. Dollars after the cabinet endorsed the sale of four
parastatals including two hotels and two processing factories,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Among the 44 parastatals to be sold, 25 are agricultural
companies which involves nine tea factories and three coffee
factories. The tea and coffee industries are Rwanda's major
foreign exchange earners.
</P>
<P>
Under the three-year (1998-2001) economic reforms program
known as ESAF, the Rwandan government is committed to privatizing
all the state-owned enterprises in a bid to reduce its
expenditure and to increase its revenues through taxation and
sales of parastatals.
</P>
<P>
Up to 1991, the Rwandan government was spending more than
seven million U.S. Dollars annually to support public enterprises
for subsidizing their operations and equipment, grants and
retrospective borrowings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
