<HEADLINE> Iran, Iraq Swap Remains of Killed Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Iraq Tuesday exchanged
remains of 53 Iranian and 134 Iraqi soldiers killed during the
1980-88 Iran-Iraq war, the Iranian official news agency IRNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
The swap took place at the Shalamcheh border crossing in
Iran's Khuzestan province, IRNA said, giving no further details
about the exchange.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report also quoted Mirfeisal Baqerzadeh,
commander of Iran's committee in charge of searching for those
missing in action (MIA), as saying that Iran has proposed joint
search with Iraq in border regions to locate remains of soldiers
killed in the war.
</P>
<P>
Baqerzadeh said that the proposals were made to Iraqi
officials during talks on Monday, adding that Tehran suggested
Sumar in Iran and Mandali in Iraq as the sites for the second
stage of the joint search operations.
</P>
<P>
The two countries recently sped up their efforts to solve the
issues of prisoners of war (POW) and MIAs. Last month, the two
countries reached an agreement on joint operations to search for
the remains of killed soldiers on both sides of the borders.
</P>
<P>
In April, the two countries swapped 5,584 Iraqi POWs with 319
Iranians. Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan said recently
that the cases of 90 percent of Iraqi and Iranian POWs have been
solved and the remaining would be settled in the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
