<HEADLINE> China Vows to Ensure Safety of Nuclear Power Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- China has vowed to guarantee the
safety of nuclear power plants as its nuclear industry moves into
a hectic year.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior official in charge of the nuclear
industry, China will be busy building its nuclear power
projects this year.
</P>
<P>
However, first of all, China will ensure the safe and stable
operation of the Qinshan and Daya Bay nuclear power plants, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country will continue to undertake a number of
nuclear power projects this year, namely, the phase 2 and 3 at
Qinshan, the projects at Ling'ao and Liangyungang.
</P>
<P>
The official urged all nuclear departments to have a greater
sense of responsibility, improve management systems, and enhance
the safety of nuclear materials and facilities.
</P>
<P>
He said the relevant parties have set up a joint meeting system
and a regular coordination meeting system to exclusively research
the construction of nuclear power projects, and solve problems
jointly and quickly.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the country's two functioning
nuclear power plants at Qinshan and Daya Bay have maintained stable
and safe operations. And both of the plants have been refueled and
overhauled a second time. So far, the two plants have generated
nearly 15 billion kilowatt hours of electricity.
</P>
<P>
Surveys have found that the amount of waste discharged by
Qinshan and Daya Bay meet government-set standards and have passed
safety checks conducted by the International Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
They posed no harm to the surrounding environment and have
helped build a good image for China's nuclear power industry,
they stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
