<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Rupee Touches All-Time Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Indian rupee became volatile
against the U.S. dollar in early trading Tuesday and dipped to an
all-time low of 42.2 to a dollar in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported from Mumbai that the
State Bank of India (SBI) had stopped propping up the rupee,
causing the currency to breach the 42 a dollar mark.
</P>
<P>
SBI had continuously supported the rupee since the union
government presented to the parliament its annual budget on June
1, which lacks measures to attract foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
The rupee opened at 41.86 a dollar, slightly lower than Monday
when it closed at 41.80 and came under severe pressure thereafter
in the absence of SBI support.
</P>
<P>
A foreign exchange dealer said in Mumbai that the rupee may be
allowed to depreciate to a certain level before possible heavy
intervention to prevent it from having a free-fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
