<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Chinese Official Urges Early Entry Into WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Sun Zhenyu today called on the international
community to let China join the World Trade Organization (WTO) as
early as possible.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar on the Asian financial crisis held today
in Beijing, Sun said the Southeast Asian financial crisis has
posed a serious challenge to China's foreign trade. However, he
added, proceeding from the overall situation of stabilizing the
Southeast Asian economy and global economy, the Chinese government
solemnly committed itself to maintaining a stable Renminbi and has
paid a high price for it.
</P>
<P>
"The responsible behavior of China has met with high acclaim
from the international community, and the best return of the
international community to China is to let China join the WTO as
early as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
Without the participation of China, the WTO will not be
complete, he noted. Its early entry into the WTO is beneficial for
the country's opening and reform process and its long-term
development, and it is also beneficial for China to contribute
more to the world in the future.
</P>
<P>
Sun analyzed in detail the impact of the financial crisis on
China's foreign trade and explained the measures adopted by the
Chinese government to cope with the challenge and reach its
economic target.
</P>
<P>
"The negative impact of the Southeast Asian financial crisis
cannot be underestimated, and the delayed consequences on China's
foreign trade sector will continue to show for a lengthy time to
come," he said. "China needs two critical conditions to meet these
challenges: one is domestic stability, the other is international
sympathy and support." 
</P>
</TEXT>
