<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight FMs Call For Nuclear Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from eight
nations Tuesday have requested in an initiative further nuclear
disarmament by the international community to ensure a world free
from nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was signed by foreign ministers from
Sweden, Brazil, Egypt, Ireland, Mexico, New Zealand, Slovenia and
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The eight countries committed themselves to the process of
continued nuclear de-commissioning to wipe out nuclear weapons
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The eight ministers also called for an international pact to
ban the production of fissionables designed to develop nuclear
weapons. And they advocated a global agreement on guarantees from
states regarding no `first use' or `no threat' with nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
Also in the initiative, the ministers called on India, Pakistan
and Israel for immediate and unconditional entry into the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty and the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
India launched five nuclear tests in May and sparked its
neighbor Pakistan to conduct a series of nuclear tests late that
month, which had cast the shadow of a nuclear arms race in South
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Unveiling the initiative, Swedish Foreign Minister Lena
Hjelm-Wallen hoped the proposal would inject new political push
for nuclear disarmament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
