<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi to Launch Own TV Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Malawi will by the end of this
year launch its own national television, Minister of Information
Sam Mpasu said in the commercial city of Blantyre Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mpasu was speaking when opening a six-week television
broadcast and production management course funded by United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organizations
(UNESCO) in preparation for the national television launch,
reported the Malawi News Agency Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Malawi never had its own television service since its
independence from Britain 34 years ago as the previous
government of Hastings Banda felt Malawians would be exposed to
"alien foreign cultures detrimental to rich Malawian culture."
</P>
<P>
But the television service, labeled by the information
minister as "a necessity for the enhancement of development and
democracy", will by December this year be in place.
</P>
<P>
Mpasu said, " I am happy that negotiations with all key
players are at very advanced stage and all effort is being made
to have actual broadcast start before the end of the year."
</P>
<P>
Part of the consignment of the transmission equipment has
already arrived. What remains is completion of the shipment of
the rest and installation, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The project that started soon after the new government came into
power in 1994 was earmarked for completion by 1996 but delayed
due to "financial constraints and complexity of TV broadcasting."
</P>
<P>
Mpasu, therefore, appealed for donor support for the provision
of some more equipment and training of staff.
</P>
<P>
Some of the technical staff including producers and camera men
have already been trained through attachments to already
existing television stations in neighboring countries like
Namibia and Zimbabwe and in Germany.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
