<HEADLINE> Song Jian Named President of China-Japan Friendship Association </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Song Jian, vice chairman of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC)
National Committee, has been appointed president of the
China-Japan Friendship Association (CJFA), official sources
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Song said he was honored to take the position at the 20th
anniversary of the signing of the Treaty for Peace and Friendship
Between China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
He said he would inherit and develop the spirit of the pioneers
in the bilateral friendship, and strive together with all
friendship groups and all walks of people from China and Japan to
accomplish the lofty ideal that friendship between the Chinese and
Japanese peoples would last for generations.
</P>
<P>
Song Jian, 66, was born in Rongcheng of Shandong Province. He
studied at Harbin Polytechnical University and Beijing Foreign
Language Institute. He then received a doctorate degree at
Moscow's Bauman Engineering Institute.
</P>
<P>
He has served as a state councillor and minister in charge of
the State Science and Technology Commission.
</P>
<P>
Song was elected vice-chairman of the CPPCC National Committee
in March. As an expert in automation and control theories, he also
serves as president of the Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE)
and is academician of the CAE and the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1963, the CJFA is a nationwide non-governmental
group.
</P>
<P>
With the support of the Chinese government and people from all
fields of China and Japan, it has founded extensive friendly and
cooperative ties with Japanese people and units in the fields of
politics, economy, culture, science and technology and education
as well as Japanese local governments.
</P>
<P>
The CJFA has contributed to the normalization of Sino-Japanese
diplomatic relations, the establishment of the Treaty for Peace
and Friendship, the advancement of mutual understanding between
the peoples of the two nations, and promotion of the long-term and
stable development of bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Sees Africa's Economic Growth Promising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUGODOUGOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The African Development Bank
(ADB) Tuesday gave a promising note for sustainable growth and
development in Africa in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
The latest forecasts indicated that gross domestic product
(GDP) growth rate in 1998 and in the medium-term will be around
four to five percent, said ADB President Omar Kabbaj in his
statement delivered to the current summit meeting of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, Africa's economic performance
continued on the positive trend, with GDP growth estimated to
have averaged 4.5 percent during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
This compared with an average of less than two percent during
the 1990-95 period, the president told the 34th OAU summit which
is to close Wednesday in the capital city of Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
GDP growth surpassed that of population with close to 40
countries experiencing positive growth in real per capita income
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Only half that number of countries had such growth rates at
the beginning of the decade, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Kabbaj, the on-going policy reforms have
contributed to reducing the overall fiscal deficits, the average
inflation rate, and the current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, overall economic performance remains
vulnerable to adverse external shocks emanating from weaker
international prices for some major primary commodities,
unfavorable weather conditions and civil strife in some
countries.
</P>
<P>
The effects of the external shocks have been mitigated by the
greater resilience associated with the macro-economic reforms
implemented by many countries.
</P>
<P>
On the domestic front, according to the ADB president, growth
should benefit from the deepening of economic reforms and the
ensuing declines in inflation and fiscal deficits, as well as
continuing improvements in the environment for private sector
development.
</P>
<P>
He admitted, however, the difference in the development of
various African countries, saying that it remains true that a
majority of African countries depend on a few agricultural and
mineral products and services.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, African countries cannot afford to be complacent,
more needs to be done to consolidate, sustain and deepen economic
development, especially with respect to reducing absolute
poverty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
