<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves New Biotechnology Research Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Union approved 154
new research projects in biotechnology on Tuesday such as gene
therapy, optimization of bioprocesses and environment restoration.
</P>
<P>
The research projects are expected to draw 138 million ECU (153
million U.S. dollars) as funding resources in cutting-edge fields
of biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
Most of the research projects are directed at improving human
health by finding new anti-microbials and by controlling the
spread of antibiotic resistance.
</P>
<P>
The new selection brought to 456 the total number of EU-funded
biotechnology research projects under its fourth framework program
between 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Future EU support for research in biotechnology will be
reinforced under the fifth framework program for the period of
1998-2002 and the research will be directed to quality of life and
living resources.
</P>
<P>
The new research projects chosen for EU funding were submitted
last October for approval by the European Commission, the
executive body of the EU.
</P>
<P>
Among the 3,366 application projects for commission funding,
most concentrate on neuroscience, immunology and vaccinology as
well as structural biology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
