<HEADLINE> China Considers P5 Meeting Successful, FM Spokesman Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The meeting in Geneva last week
achieved the anticipated result and laid a basis for efforts by
the international community to resolve the South Asian issue,
Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Zhu Bangzao said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a routine press conference here today, Zhu said that at the
joint proposal by both China and the United States, the foreign
ministers of the Five Permanent Members of the United Nations
Security Council (P5) held a meeting on June 4 in Geneva for an
exchange of views on the nuclear issue and the current situation
in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The P5 meeting denounced nuclear tests by India and Pakistan,
he said, and the five nations are deeply concerned with the
tension caused by the tests, which can undermine peace and
stability in this region.
</P>
<P>
The meeting coordinated the five members' positions on issues
of ceasing the nuclear and missile race between India and
Pakistan, reinforcing peace and stability in South Asia and
preventing the further spread of nuclear weapons, Zhu said. After
the meeting, he added, the five member nations issued a joint
statement reflecting their common stand.
</P>
<P>
The meeting ended with anticipated results, showing the five
nations' unanimous stance on major world issues, especially on the
non-recognition of India and Pakistan's nuclear power status and
resumption of peace and stability in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The meeting kicked off a process, so that the basis has been
laid for the international community to work to resolve the
South Asian issue, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that Pakistan welcomed the outcome of the P5
meeting, whereas India issued a statement refusing to accept it.
</P>
<P>
China is calling for India to respond to the concerns of the
international community, so as to resume peace and stability in
the region as soon as possible, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
