<HEADLINE> China's Industrial Output Slightly Increases in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial added value
reached 168.1 billion yuan in May, rising by eight percent on a
year-on-year basis, according to an economic report released today
by the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The official statistics show that the country realized a total
industrial added value of 776.8 billion yuan in the first five
months this year, a year-on-year increase of 7.9 percent. The
industrial sales ratio in May hit 95.6 percent, almost the same
level as the corresponding period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report also indicates that the industrial added value of
state-owned industry in May reached 76 billion yuan, increasing by
2.5 percent over the same period of last year; that of
collective-owned industry, 43.6 billion yuan, rising by 7.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth rate of 18 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions in May was higher than in April, with that of
nine provinces including Hebei, Shanxi, Jilin, Jiangsu and Hunan
two percentage points higher than the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Although the industrial output picked up in May, the sales are
not brisk enough because of sluggish domestic and overseas
market. Therefore, it is necessary to stimulate the market demand
and improve the economic efficiency, according to an official of
the State Statistics Bureau. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
