<HEADLINE> Rebels Burn 50 Students to Death in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- At least 50 students were burnt to
death and more were feared to have been abducted when rebels of
Allied Democratic Front (ADF) Monday launched a surprise attack
on the Kichwamba National Technical Institute in Kabarole
District in western Uganda.
</P>
<P>
A New Vision report Tuesday quoted survivors as saying that
some 200 to 300 rebels rushed into the school at 5:30 a.m. Monday
and locked student dormitories before setting them ablaze with
petrol.
</P>
<P>
By the time the rebels arrived at the college there were only
10 security personnel, army soldiers who were subsequently
overpowered.
</P>
<P>
Five unidentified civilians were shot dead in one of the worst
rebel attacks in the district.
</P>
<P>
Three out of the seven halls of residence at the college are
reported to be completely gutted by the fire and cries were
heard.
</P>
<P>
"The wailing amid sporadic gunfire could be heard in Kichwamba
trading center," said a terrified resident.
</P>
<P>
The fire kept burning up to late afternoon and the school was
indefinitely closed, said Chemasuet Ndiwa, acting resident
district commissioner.
</P>
<P>
Another report here said the rebels' goal was to abduct all
the students allegedly to bolster their manpower resource.
However, when they met with resistance, the rebels decided to
burn the students.
</P>
<P>
Government forces have intensified operations against ADF
rebels in western mountains recently. As retaliation, the
bandits abducted civilians and threatened with terrorism in
cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
