<HEADLINE> International Agency Anticipating Drop in the Demand For Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The International Energy Agency (IEA)
said here on Tuesday that the worldwide demand for oil in the
second quarter of this year is expected to drop by 510,000
barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
In a monthly report, the IEA, which is headquartered in Paris,
said the reason for the drop is because of the Asian financial
crisis and a weak demand for oil in the 29 member countries of the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
On June 4, in response to the weakening demand, the oil
ministers of Saudi Arabia, Mexico and Venezuela, all major oil
production countries, decided in Amsterdam to cut production by
450,000 barrels per day beginning July 1.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in March, the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) reached an agreement to cut production by 1.245
million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices have been dropping throughout the world since the
beginning of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> George Bush Says Asian Economy will Recover Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. President George Bush
said today that the Asian financial crisis will not last long
and that the Asian economy will soon be revitalized.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar on the Asian financial crisis, Bush
described the crisis as "growing pains," and said the Asian
economy will be even stronger after the crisis ends.
</P>
<P>
"China's action in dealing with the crisis is responsible and
bold," said the 74-year-old former U.S. president, who is here as
guest of the Chinese People's Association for Friendship with
Foreign Countries.
</P>
<P>
China received real recognition both for its active engagement
in providing "tangible assistance" to help regional economies
recover, and for its willingness to make the "tough decision" not
to devalue its currency, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese economy will have a growing impact on
the global economy because of its size and growth rate.
</P>
<P>
He added that China will become fully integrated into
the global economy and, at that time, it will play an even greater
role in terms of politics, economy and security.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China still faces a great challenge on the road
head, he said, and that great skill and considerable political
courage will be required.
</P>
<P>
Bush -- who visited Thailand, Singapore and Hong Kong before
he came to China -- told the audience that it is not an Asian
financial crisis, but a crisis which is centered in Asia, and that
its effects are being increasingly felt around the world. "Global
economic interdependence is an undeniable reality," he said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that it is also a crisis to which governments
and business communities around the world need to respond, not in
Asia's interest, but in their own self-interest.
</P>
<P>
Bush, who has visited China each year since stepping down as
president in 1992, said that the financial system and banking section
problems are a reflection of more profound problems in the broader
economic system, which are more psychological than economic or
financial.
</P>
<P>
He said that the psychology of government leaders and investors
is very important. Political stability will help restore
investors' confidence which is necessary for economic recovery, he
said, and that economic recovery is indispensable to political
stability.
</P>
<P>
Bush said that Chinese leaders deserve a lot of credit for the
implementation of the "one country, two systems" formula.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident of the future of Hong Kong politically and
economically," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
