<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Ratify Human Rights Conventions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will ratify a number of
international conventions on human rights, including one against
torture, Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will ratify the conventions in stages in the next five
years," he told reporters after meeting President B. J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
The president, he said, is also expected to launch a national
action plan on human rights on June 25 as a follow-up to
agreements reached during the Second World Conference on Human
Rights in Vienna in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Under one of these agreements, each country should form an
action plan on human rights, elaborating on how it intends to
implement human rights.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said the Indonesian government, in cooperation with the
National Human Rights Commission, has established a committee on
human rights to work on the action plan.
</P>
<P>
He reported to Habibie that everything is ready and the
president agreed to launch the action plan on June 25.
</P>
<P>
The date, June 25, was chosen because it is the same date the
Vienna Declaration was adopted five years ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Alatas, Indonesia will first ratify the
international instruments on human rights before disseminating
information and educating people on the concept and principles of
human rights and implementing human rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
