<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Undecided on Referendum on Pullback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said Tuesday that no referendum has been set on the
further Israeli troops pullback from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Israel Radio, Netanyahu said that he was not
yet committed to holding such a referendum in the current
situation.
</P>
<P>
He was convinced that his decision on Israeli troops
redeployment would be supported by a majority of the public and
the Knesset (parliament), Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
Some Knesset members have suggested that the prime minister
could bypass the cabinet and presented the withdrawal issue
directly to the public in face of mounting pressure from the
U.S. on one side, and from right-wing members in his coalition on
the other.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and the Palestinians are pressing Netanyahu's
government to accept the U.S. proposal to withdraw troops from 13
percent more of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But the right-wing members in the coalition, who refuse to
yield even an inch to the Palestinians, threatened to topple
Netanyahu if he went ahead with the pullback.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been deeply stranded
due to Israel's intransigence on the redeployment issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu urged the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) to live up to its commitments to the security of Israel in
order that the two sides could reach an agreement on the
redeployment in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Before meeting a U.S. business delegation Tuesday, Netanyahu
reiterated that there has been some progress in the negotiations
with the PNA. But he did not elaborate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
