<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Boost Unit Trust Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim Tuesday assured the Federation of Malaysian
Unit Trust Managers that the government will consider tax
exemptions and other incentives to boost the unit trust industry.
</P>
<P>
A vibrant unit trust industry would boost the capital market
through injection of liquidity that would prevent the market from
being too vulnerable to the sudden outflow of funds, Anwar, who is
also finance minister, told a seminar on unit trusts here.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed surprise at the unit trust industry's low
contribution to the market capitalization of the Kuala Lumpur
Stock Exchange, which now stands at 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
He urged the public to buy the units now to take advantage of
the low prices since they would surely gain from capital
appreciation when the market recovers, assuring that the
government will strive to protect the interests of unit trust
holders.
</P>
<P>
The fall in stock prices since the middle of last year has led
to a decline in the value of unit trusts, to 43 billion ringgit
(about 10.91 billion U.S. dollars) on March 31, 1998, from 56
billion ringgit (about 14.21 billion dollars) at the start of the
regional economic crisis, Anwar noted.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the importance of public confidence in the
country's economic and financial system, saying the government
would take whatever steps to return the country's economic
fundamentals to a firmer footing.
</P>
<P>
He also called for greater professionalism and consolidation in
the management of unit trusts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
