<HEADLINE> HK Exhibition in Memory of Late Chinese Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition entitled "A Premier
Respected by His People" opened here on Tuesday in commemoration
of the centenary of the birth of the late Chinese Premier Zhou
Enlai.
</P>
<P>
This is the first exhibition ever held in Hong Kong in honor of
a late Chinese leader.
</P>
<P>
The exhibits attracted a total of 900,000 visitors while they
were displayed in Beijing for three months from February, a record
number for years for any exhibitions in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Hong Kong-based China Cultural City Limited,
the Chinese-language newspaper Ta Kung Pao and the National Museum
of Chinese Modern and Contemporary History, more than 300 exhibits
including a replica of Zhou's former office in Xihuating in
Beijing's Forbidden City, had been shipped to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, born in Huai'an, Jiangsu Province, in March 1898, died of
cancer in January 1976. As one of the founders of the Chinese
Communist Party, the People's Republic of China and the People's
Liberation Army, Zhou had enjoyed high esteem at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Zhou visited Hong Kong three times during the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
After the closure of the exhibition here on June 14, some of
the exhibits will be moved to Macao for a five-day display
starting on June 18.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
