<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibition to Mark Centennial of China's Bourgeois Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition to mark the
centennial of the 1898 Reform Movement, a bourgeois democratic
reform in Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), will be held in the Palace
Museum in Beijing from June 11 to September 21, coincidentally the
time of the reform movement 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
On June 11, 1898, Emperor Guangxu adopted the reform advocation
of bourgeois reformers Kang Youwei and Liang Qichao, and announced
the reform policies, in order to save the national crisis that
China would be partitioned by imperialist powers.
</P>
<P>
The reform was carried out for only 103 days until September 21
when Empress Dowager Cixi staged a palace coup d'etat. Emperor
Guangxu was imprisoned, and the reformers were arrested and killed.
</P>
<P>
With an investment of 200,000 yuan (24,000 US dollars), the
five-part exhibition will show 77 items of cultural relics, 105
pieces of historical documents and 153 pictures, which give an
overall introduction on China's social conditions, the reform
movement and people's efforts to save the country at that time.
</P>
<P>
Many items on display are original historical archives and
relics, including Emperor Guangxu's edict of reform, as well as
the letter the reformers submitted to the emperor.
</P>
<P>
Qin Guojing, vice-director of the China No. 1 Historical
Archives Museum, said the 1898 Reform Movement was the first
movement of emancipating minds and challenging the feudal system
in China's modern history, noting that although it ended in
failure, the movement pioneered the political reform in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the exhibition is to remind people of the misery
China suffered 100 years ago and to make them carry forward the
patriotism and devotedness of the reformers, Qin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Explosion Kills 1 Injures 5 in Northern Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- One staff member was killed and five
others wounded in a possibly gas explosion at noon Tuesday in a
hospital in Rasht, Iran's northern province of Gilan, the official
news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Head of the services department of the Totonkaran hospital, who
was not identified, was quoted as saying that two of the injuried
were at critical condition.
</P>
<P>
He said that none of the patients in the hospital or
outpatients were affected by the explosion, who cause has not yet
been determined.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said that the blast might have been caused by a leakage of
gas at the heating installations of the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Window panes of the hospital and nearby buildings were
shattered by the blast, and the heating installations of the
hospital were completely destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, a bomb went off at the Islamic Revolution Court
in Tehran, killing three people and injuring a number of
others. Iran's outlawed Mujahideen Khalq Organization (MKO)
claimed responsibility for the blast.
</P>
<P>
The explosion caused condemnation on the MKO, Iran's biggest
armed opposition group based in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
