<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, China to Boost Investment, Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Industrialists and exporters from
European Union countries and China gathered here at a seminar on
Tuesday to discuss ways to boost investment and bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
A total of 250 businessmen from Britain, France, Germany, the
Netherlands, Italy, Belgium and China compared notes on the
investment environment and trade issues in China.
</P>
<P>
Sir Leon Brittan, vice-president of the European Commission,
told seminar participants that uncertainty is the single biggest
deterrent to foreign investment in the Asian country.
</P>
<P>
He said the problem is in the way various local,
regional and national public administrations oversee the large
number of rules, conditions and terms which govern commercial
activities.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president of the commission, the executive body of the
15-nation European Union, said that accession to the World Trade
Organization would enhance China's efforts to attract foreign
direct investment as well as boost the country's pace and depth of
domestic economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Shi Guangsheng, the Chinese minister of foreign trade and
economic cooperation, told the seminar that the Chinese economy
has maintained a favorable momentum for the past 20 years since
the start of reform and opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
The country, the minister said, deepened economic reform,
extended the opening-up process, improved macro-regulations and
managed a `soft landing' while maintaining high growth and low
inflation.
</P>
<P>
Shi cited China's stable currency during the financial crisis
in East Asia as both a demonstration of the country's ability to
do so and the contribution it made in stabilizing Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
He promised that China's industrial tariffs would be reduced to
the average level of developing countries by the year 2000 and
would be reduced to 10 percent by 2005.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is China's third largest trading
partner. Trade volume last year grew by 8.4 percent to reach 43
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The EU member states now hold 8,352 investment projects in
China with a pledged capital input of 31.47 billion dollars. The
EU is the country's fifth largest investor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
