<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Down Amid Concerns Over Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
deteriorated on Tuesday amid ongoing uncertainty surrounding the
embattled Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries Index ignored a stronger Wall
Street overnight and gains in Tokyo to fall to its lowest close in
almost four months.
</P>
<P>
It ended 18.9 points softer at 2623.9, just above its February
16 finish of 2621.2.
</P>
<P>
"It's been a disappointing performance in view of the strong
offshore markets," Morgans Stockbroking's Simon Reed said.
</P>
<P>
"Investors continue to be concerned about the state of the
Australian dollar and interest rate implications but most
economists believe there will be no upward movement in domestic
interest rates."
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries had opened a little firmer as the Australian
dollar gyrated in early trade around the time of the Reserve Bank
of Australia's money market position announcement early Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
However, no change to monetary policy saw the local currency
slipping back below the 60 U.S. cent level and the stock market
followed in kind.
</P>
<P>
Stable commodity prices failed to prop up the local resources
sector, with the All Resources Index easing 5.9 points to 1068.3.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index came off 34.7 points to 4560.7.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto jumped 34 cents to 19.67 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company earlier announced it would pay 400 million U.S.
dollars for the Jacobs Ranch coal mine in the Powder River Basin
of Wyoming in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The deal adds another low-cost open-cut coal mine to the Powder
River Basin portfolio of Rio's wholly-owned subsidiary Kennecott
Energy.
</P>
<P>
Leading Australian company BHP slipped 11 cents to 13.54
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index rose 10.1 points to 1124.2 on the back of a
stronger bullion price. The precious metal was trading 3.2 U.S.
dollars higher at 295.7 U.S. dollars an ounce in Sydney by 17:00
(Australian Eastern Standard Time), Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The banking index faltered because of the perception of a rise
in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank of Australia dropped 32 cents to 18
Australian dollars, Westpac bank lost 24 cents to 9.55 Australian
dollars, National Australia Bank dipped 3.6 cents to 21.754
Australian dollars and ANZ bank managed to add 7 cents to reach
10.85 Australian dollars on a heavy turnover of 8.2 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 279.7 million shares valued at 460.32
million U.S. dollars. Rises of 355 were behind falls of 728.
</P>
</TEXT>
