<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Abacha Buried in Kano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Late Nigerian head of state, general
Sani Abacha, who died in the early hours of monday, has been
buried in Kano city, his home town in the northern Nigeria, local
media reports said.
</P>
<P>
Abacha's body was conveyed to Kano on board a presidential jet
which reportedly arrived at the Kano Airport at about 7:30 p.m.
on Monday with a delegation that includes former chief of defense
staff and now the new Head of State, General Abudusalam Abubakar,
and the minister of the federal capital territory and other top
government officials, security heads and family members and
friends.
</P>
<P>
The remains of Abacha, wrapped in simple white cloth, was
brought out of the plane in a stretcher and moved into a peugeot
ambulence waiting there.
</P>
<P>
A special prayer was held for him at about 8:00 p.m. at the
state race course ground.
</P>
<P>
Abacha was eventually buried at about 8:45 p.m. in his
personal residence on Gidado Road in Kano City, according to
islamic rites.
</P>
<P>
Abacha reportedly died of heart attack at about 3:00 a.m.
Monday in the presidential viall Aso Rock in Abuja. Doctors tried
several hours to save his life but failed.
</P>
<P>
The presidential villa was sealed off by military men in the
earnly morning of Monday. Staff who came to work were ordered
back.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's highest ruling body, the Provisional Ruling
Council (PRC) began an emergency meeting at about 12:00 p.m..
</P>
<P>
At the end of its meeting at about 5:00 p.m., the PRC said in
a statement signed by Abubakar that Abacha died in sleep in the
early morning of that day, without giving exact reasons of the
death.
</P>
<P>
Upon returning from the burial in Kano, the PRC reconvened at
about 11:00 p.m., which ended at about 2:15 a.m. Tuesday morning
with a decision to name Abubakar as the new leader.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar was immediately sworn in by the Chief Justice of the
federation, Justic Mohammed Uwais.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar, hitherto a major-general, was promoted to the rank
of a full general at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar has annunced a seven-day national mourning in honor
of Abacha. He will address the nation in due course.
</P>
<P>
General Abacha, 54, took over power in November 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to the transition to civil rule program announced by
him in 1995, Abacha is expected to handover power to an elected
civilian government in October this year.
</P>
<P>
In April, Nigeria's five political parties adopted Abacha as
their consensus candidate for the presidential election scheduled
for August 1. But Abacha has been silent on the issue until his
death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
