<HEADLINE> Mozambican Minister Hails Ties with Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The German government provided 70 million Deutsche Marks
(about 39 million U.S. Dollars) in the 1997/1998 fiscal year, in
which 35 million Marks (about 19.5 Million Dollars) are for
donation, 20 million (11.2 million Dollars) are for technological
cooperation and 15 million Marks (8.38 million Dollars) are for
financial cooperation, the Noticias daily newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister also revealed that Germany has participated in
many projects in Mozambique, including those in the areas of
mining and energy, transport and telecommunications, public
engineering, housing, education and de-mining.
</P>
<P>
The past bilateral cooperation mostly focused on rehabilitating
projects, Simao said, adding that now it will shift to development
programs such as the rebuilding of a large granary in Maputo
city.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Simao expressed the government's hope that Germany
will play a more vigorous role in the international sphere to
help eliminate his country's foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Currently Mozambique's foreign debt stands at 5.7 billion U.S.
Dollars. The international community has pledged to cut 80
percent of it starting from June 1999. Nonetheless, Mozambique
wishes the debt could be completely written off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
