<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Remains Below 60 U.S. Cent Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar continued to
flounder below the 60 U.S. cent level Tuesday despite efforts by
leading Australian ministers to talk it up.
</P>
<P>
After a tide of selling by U.S. hedge funds which knocked the
currency down to 12-year lows in recent sessions, little fresh
selling emerged on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 59.81 U.S. cents at the end of
Asian trading on Tuesday, down from 59.68 U.S. cents on Monday.
</P>
<P>
But after traversing a tight range of 59.63-60.10 U.S. cents in
Sydney, the local dollar was again suffering at 59.61 U.S. cents
as overseas markets opened early Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The unit was still well above its post float low of 57.10 U.S.
cents reached on July 28, 1986.
</P>
<P>
Jon Sutton, a senior manager of corporate foreign exchange with
the Commonwealth Bank of Australia, said trading had been a lot
quieter Tuesday than in previous sessions.
</P>
<P>
Further losses had been expected for the local currency on
Tuesday after the large sell-offs in the past few days, with the
fate of the currency remaining in the hands of U.S. hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
"That depends on the resolve of these so-called hedge funds --
if they continue to sell, the Aussie could still make new lows,"
Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
Dealers continued to attribute the weakness in the Australian
dollar to lower commodity prices and the fall of the Japanese yen
against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The link between the Japanese and Australian currencies is due
to Australia's trade dependence on Japan, which takes around 20
percent of Australia's goods exports.
</P>
<P>
The weakness in the yen reflects Japan's poor growth position
and the difficulties faced by its banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Michael Workman, foreign exchange strategist with the
Commonwealth Bank of Australia, said any recovery in the
Australian dollar would require some improvement in the Japanese
economy and a stronger Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The conjecture now was whether the Reserve Bank of Australia,
the nation's central bank, will raise interest rates to defend the
currency after reportedly spending around 3 billion Australian
dollars (about 1.8 billion U.S. dollars) in attempts to smooth the
unit's relentless downward drift.
</P>
<P>
The local dollar's weakness continued despite Australian
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer telling New York businessmen
that the domestic economy was in good shape.
</P>
<P>
Australian Treasurer Peter Costello also talked about the
strength of the Australian dollar and stressed the fundamentals of
the Australian economy, including strong growth, low inflation and
a projected budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, on the foreign exchange cross rates, the Australian
dollar was buying 84.06 Japanese yen from 83.96 yen and 1.0626
German marks from 1.0629 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
