<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Against Any Move to Amend Existing GATT/WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Tuesday any move
to amend the existing GATT/WTO rules should be treated with great
caution and should be rejected in view of the eminent danger of
legitimizing trade instruments to address environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah
Aziz said Tuesday that there had been proposals to amend current
World Trade Organization (WTO) rules especially Article XX of the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) 1994 so as to accord
recognition of environment protection as a ground to impede trade.
</P>
<P>
However, Malaysia views that any move to amend the existing
GATT/WTO rules, whether by amplification or making them clearer,
should be treated with great caution and should be rejected in
view of the eminent danger of legitimizing trade instruments to
address environmental problems, she said in a speech at the WTO
Regional Seminar on Trade and Environment here, which was read by
her ministry's parliamentary secretary Ahmad Kamaruzaman Mohd
Baria.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said it was necessary to emphasize that environmental
protection should be pursued in the context of sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
She reiterated that Malaysia was not oblivious to environmental
protection, saying "in fact Malaysia's active participation in the
relevant regional and international fora on environment
cooperation reflects the country's concern and environmental
protection."
</P>
<P>
Malaysia was, however, disappointed that some developed
countries continued to apply environmental policy measures
unilaterally and in a discriminatory manner out of political
expediency rather than by consensus based on objective technical
and economic justification, she said.
</P>
<P>
They would later change the ground rules of trade competition
and reduce competitiveness through added cost loaded on to the
producers or exporters, she said, adding "What is of greater
concern to the trading community including Malaysia is that such
environmental measures are conveniently used as a covert form of
trade protectionism to circumvent the WTO system." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
