<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Opposes Foreign Intervention in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin
Jovanovic has said that his country was firmly opposed to any form
of foreign military intervention in the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Jovanovic, who is here to attend the two-day Balkan Foreign
Ministerial Meeting starting Monday, told Xinhua that the Kosovo
crisis was "an internal issue of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia" and should be kept from foreign influence.
</P>
<P>
"There is no need, no space and no acceptance of foreign
interference in such an internal issue," Jovanovic said.
</P>
<P>
He urged that the Kosovo crisis be solved through "political
dialog" between the Serbian government and ethnic Albanians of
Kosovo "within the framework of sovereignty and integrity of
Serbia."
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, we do not see the reason of any pressure and
interference (from foreign countries)," he said, adding that
foreign military intervention will not contribute to a solution to
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The tensions in Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia, have
heightened since February when bloody clashes erupted between
Serbian police and ethnic Albanians who demand independence from
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and some European countries have indicated that
military operations might be taken into consideration if the
bloodshed in Kosovo continues to escalate.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministers from the Balkan countries have exchanged
views on ways of settling the issue, which threatens the security
and stability of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
