<HEADLINE> Russia's Top Statisticians Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Head of Russia's State Committee for
Statistics (SCS), Yuri Yurkov, and his first deputy were arrested
Monday night for allegedly distorting statistics to help big
companies evade tax.
</P>
<P>
Also arrested were heads of the committee's computer center in
what was believed to be the first criminal case against such
high-ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
The Government Information Directorate said they were arrested
for systematically distorting statistical data on large firms and
companies, enabling the firms to dodge tax payments.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported that 1 million U.S. dollars
in cash was discovered in Yurkov's home during a search Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
The case was handled by the Federal Security Service and the
Office for Prosecutor-General. Yurkov has been under investigation
and field surveillance since April.
</P>
<P>
Tax evasion by enterprises has long been a headache annoying
the Russian authorities. It was reported that only 17 percent of
the country's enterprises fully pay their taxes on time and that
up to 33 percent of the enterprises never pay any taxes.
Government officials' collaboration with owners of enterprises has
exacerbated the situation.
</P>
<P>
Yurkov was appointed head of the SCS in October 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
