<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange closed higher Tuesday on selective buying
interests, particularly on bluechips.
</P>
<P>
Market sentiment was quite weak in the afternoon session as
dealers said players were concerned about the weakening ringgit
against the U.S. dollar and on fears that Japanese yen would slip
further against the greenback and affect regional markets and
currencies.
</P>
<P>
However, they said the ringgit's recovery to the 3.94 level
from the 4.0 level on profit taking on the greenback lent support
to the equities market and some offshore funds were also seen
taking advantage of the cheaper share prices to bargain hunt for
good stocks.
</P>
<P>
The announcement by Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister
Anwar Ibrahim Tuesday that the government would consider tax and
other incentives for the unit trust industry also triggered some
buying interests towards the close.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the 100-quality stocks Composite Index rose 7.85
to 505.64, the all-share Emas Index added 1.07 points to 129.53,
the Industrial Index added 0.55 of a point to 988.99 while the
Second Board Index slipped 0.18 of a point to 108.87.
</P>
<P>
Gainers led losers by 317 to 211, 186 counters were unchanged
and 206 counters were untraded.
</P>
<P>
The day's turnover was 84.216 million shares valued at 179.739
million ringgit (about 45.619 million U.S. dollars) against 99.174
million shares valued at 225.305 million ringgit (about 57.184
million U.S. dollars) on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The main board turnover eased to 77.732 million shares worth
169.329 million ringgit (about 42.9769 million U.S. dollars) from
Monday's 93.673 million shares valued at 217.093 million ringgit
(about 55.0997 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover rose to 6.484 million shares valued
at 11.411 million ringgit (about 2.8961 million U.S. dollars) from
5.501 million shares worth at 8.212 million ringgit (about 2.0842
million U.S. dollars) on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals amounted to 5.186 million shares worth 15.882
million ringgit (about 4.0309 million U.S. dollars) against
Monday's 5.062 million shares valued at 9.736 million ringgit
(about 2.471 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
