<HEADLINE> Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines Undergoes Major </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM) is undergoing a major shake-up with far-reaching effects
at both corporate head office and its operating divisions.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia Daily Mail Tuesday quoted Mines Minister
Siamukayumbu Siamujaye as announcing Monday that as part of ZCCM
privatization process, expatriate staff have had their contracts
terminated at five of the divisions where management has been
restructured.
</P>
<P>
He said the changes at Nchanga, where division general manager
Robert Russell has reportedly been dismissed, are part of the
changes affecting the other divisions like Nkana, Konkola and
Mufulira.
</P>
<P>
Changes will also be made at head office of ZCCM, he said.
</P>
<P>
The contracts of the expatriates have been terminated in the
normal manner and nothing has been abrogated in their contracts,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the company's staff is being rationalized
to prepare it for privatization.
</P>
<P>
On the privatization of Nchanga and Nkana mines, two biggest
ones in the copper-producing country, the minister said that
negotiations for the sale of the two are going on smoothly with
the "prospective buyers" which might include the Kafue Consortium.
</P>
<P>
The government discontinued the negotiations with the Kafue
Consortium in April because of the disagreements over the cost of
the two mines. 
</P>
