<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Enforces Laws for Maritime Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is enforcing laws to
make its maritime industry more professional and prepared to face
the challenges ahead, Transport Minister Ling Liong Sik said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new Malaysia Shipping Act, to serve as a single uniform law
for the country's entire shipping industry, is in the final stages
of drafting and will replace the current Merchant Shipping
Ordinances passed in 1952 and 1960 with one each for Peninsular
Malaysia, Sabah and Sarawak, he said when opening the 4th biennial
International Maritime Conference in Subang near here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 people are attending the two-day conference with the
theme " Maritime Industry: Meeting New &AMP; Changing Demand
Conditions in Asia."
</P>
<P>
The minister said the new Act's objective is to ensure that the
shipping laws of Malaysia are up-to-date and are kept abreast of
international laws and practices.
</P>
<P>
Ling said a new Carriage of Goods by Sea Act was also being
drafted to update the liability regime for sea transport and adopt
the Hague Visby Rules of 1968 to replace the current Hague Rules
of 1924 enacted in 1950.
</P>
<P>
Ling said the International Ship Management (ISM) Code would be
implemented from July 1 this year for bulk carriers and tankers
while for other ships such as container and cargo by 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
