<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Pilot Shot Dead in Car in Downtown Dar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Zhang Dacheng)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 9 (Xinhua) - The killing of a senior
Tanzanian pilot driving in downtown Dar es Salaam on Monday has
shocked his colleagues, the Public Relations Manager of the Air
Tanzania Corporation (ATC) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ATC Public Relations Manager, Innocent Mungy, said that
Elzeus Rugeyamba Rutazaha, a 45-year-old First Officer of the ATC
Boeing Fleet, was shot and killed while his car stopped at a
traffic light by two robbery suspects armed with a sub-machine
gun and a pistol at about 11:00 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
The only passenger in the car, Alex Kapama, a retired army
officer, said that the two strangers smashed the car windows and
shot Rutazaha in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
"They then grabbed our two briefcases and disappeared," said
Kapama, who was treated for minor bruises on the hands in the
Muhimbili Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
He said that earlier on their way to the city center, Rutazaha
stopped at a branch of the National Bank of Commerce (1997)
Limited. "I don't know whether he was withdrawing or depositing
some money."
</P>
<P>
Mungy said the deceased, who had joined the State-own ATC for
15 years with 5,000 flying hours, was off-duty following a flight
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"He is a gentleman. He is very helpful to others. His death
has shocked all of us," said Mungy, adding that he is survived by
a wife and three children.
</P>
<P>
Buka Kibona, the acting Dar es Salaam Regional Police
Commander, confirmed the incident, saying the police were looking
for the unidentified armed persons who disappeared in their own
car soon after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
With a staff of 653, the ATC owns two Boeing 737-200 and two
Forkker Friendship 27. It also rents a Boeing 737-300 from
foreign airlines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
