<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Class For Gifted Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 9 (Xinhua)-- With her child-like smile, Zhang Junni
looks just like any other high school student -- but in just two
months, the 20-year-old girl will graduate with honors from the
Chinese University of Science and Technology and go on to graduate
studies in the United Sates.
</P>
<P>
Zhang is one of 710 students there from across the country,
with higher than average intelligence, whose scores on the
national university entrance exams were as much as a hundred
points higher than admission requirements for the best
universities.
</P>
<P>
They were below the age of 15 when enrolled in the "young
genius class", most of them having skipped several grades during
their grade school years.
</P>
<P>
In the past twenty years, 550 students from this class have
graduated from the university with bachelors degrees, and 72
percent have gone on to grad school at home and abroad. More than
a hundred have already got PhDs and are doing scientific research
or international business.
</P>
<P>
Shi Zhan, who entered the class at 13, made his mark by solving
a difficult mathematics problem during PhD studies abroad, and
now, at the age of 30, is advising PhD students in France.
</P>
<P>
Huang Qing, another gifted child, is now the vice-president of
a big-name securities firm on Wall Street, and one of the few
Chinese who have walked into a senior leadership position in the
financial business in the United States.
</P>
<P>
These young people all have one thing in common: they like to
meet challenges and do pioneering researches.
</P>
<P>
A young botanist, Zhong Yang, is involved in a dozen national
research projects at the Chinese Academy of Sciences. The former
member of the young genius class has done work in systematic
cytobiology, using computers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
