<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Moves to Address Computer Millennium Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's private sector and
government institutions in the computer industry have already put
up strategies to address the challenges of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Tuesday quoted NCR Computers accounts
manager Jacqueline Mwenya as saying that her company has put up
strategies in place as far back as 1997 to avoid the millennium
bug, which will cause havoc in the computer industry in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
"As a major computer company, we have been in constant touch
with our suppliers. Our clients on the other hand have been
advised on the expectations of the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
"Our strategies include the replacement of hardware that are
too old with newer machines. We also upgrade machines that are
compliant," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that all non-compliant computers will still be used
in less critical areas such as homes or schools where they can be
used as teaching aids.
</P>
<P>
Comelius Musonda, Director of Commercial Services at Zambia
Telecommunications Corportation (ZAMTEL), said that ZAMTEL has
put up a committee to look into the problem of the year 2000
challenge.
</P>
<P>
"We are a high-tech organization and have already put in place
measures to ensure that all our computers are compliant by the
year 2000. At the moment, our position is encouraging as we have
equipment that is four digits. What remains is to upgrade the
two digits equipment to make it compliant," said Musonda.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a source close to the government as
saying that a national policy document on computers has been put
in place and guidelines will be issued.
</P>
<P>
The sources also revealed that on the global basis, the cost
of upgrading, replacing or redeveloping and retiring
non-compliant equipment will be the range to 600 billion U.S.
Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
