<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Parliament Approves Administrative Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Japan's upper house of parliament
enacted Tuesday a government-proposed administrative reform bill
designed to streamline government ministries and agencies.
</P>
<P>
The bill was adopted at a plenary session of the House of
Councillors by a majority backed by the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party, the Social Democratic Party and the New Party Sakigake.
</P>
<P>
The largest opposition Democratic Party of Japan, the Komei,
the Japanese Communist Party and the Liberal Party were against
the bill high on Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's reform agenda.
</P>
<P>
The more powerful House of Representatives, or the lower house
of parliament, had already approved the measure.
</P>
<P>
The legislation shows a timetable for reorganizing the 22
ministries and agencies into a Cabinet Office plus 12 ministries
and agencies within five years, preferably by January 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
The bill proposes the establishment of the Cabinet Office to
strengthen the cabinet's functions, and defines the major duties
and functions of the 12 new ministries.
</P>
<P>
It also stipulates that power shall be given to the prime
minister to propose the agendas for cabinet meetings, instead of
the current system with bureaucrats dictating the agendas.
</P>
<P>
Administrative reform is one of the six main reforms proposed
by Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Travelers Abroad Grow Slower in 1997, White Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A record number of Japanese traveled
abroad in 1997, but the growth fell sharply from the previous
year, said a government white paper on tourism released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The annual report shows that 16.8 million Japanese went
overseas in 1997, up 110,000, or 0.6 percent, from 1996. In
comparison, the growth had been about 10 percent since 1994.
</P>
<P>
The slower rate of growth was attributed to Japan's sluggish
economy and the depreciation of the yen, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Of the 16.8 million Japanese, 13.7 million went abroad as
tourists for sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the most popular destination for Japanese
travelers, which was visited by 5.3 million people, followed by
South Korea (1.6 million), mainland China (one million), and
China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (910,000).
</P>
<P>
The number of foreigners who visited Japan in 1997 was a
record-high of 4.2 million, up 9.9 percent from 1996, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
