<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank to Look Into Cash Flow Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
said Tuesday that it will seek the help of the National Bureau of
Investigation (NBI) to look into the cash flow problems of two
banks it ordered to shut down earlier.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Governor Alberto Reyes told reporters that the central
bank will ask the NBI to help find out if some officers of the two
banks were involved in securing loans for directors, officers,
stockholders and related interest persons (DOSRI) in excess of
what the central bank allows.
</P>
<P>
The central bank ordered the closure of the Commonwealth
Savings and Loan Bank and Richmond Bank which faced serious cash
flow problems.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has yet to determine whether it is the
excessive DOSRI loans that eventually resulted in the cash flow
problems of the two banks, Reyes said.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said if the central bank's fact-finding team is able to
establish that there was really mismanagement on the part of the
officers and directors, the central bank has no choice but file
necessary suits against those directly or indirectly involved in
the mess.
</P>
<P>
Under the central bank's rule, DOSRI loans generally should not
exceed the bank's capital funds or 15 percent of the bank's total
loan portfolio, whichever is lower.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said that the central bank is recommending some
legislative measures that will impose stiffer sanctions against
officers, directors and stockholders of banks who may have
violated the DOSRI rules of the government.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is monitoring the banking activities of at
least 17 banks which are believed to be experiencing cash flow
problems.
</P>
<P>
However, central bank officials did not attribute these
problems to the lingering effects of the currency crisis in the
region.
</P>
<P>
But they believed that these problems were caused by
mismanagement and excessive DOSRI loans made by some officers,
directors and stockholders of these banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Still Attractive to Investors: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia would continue to be
attractive to foreign investors despite the regional economic
turmoil, International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The basic pragmatic policy still prevails and policies
governing equity structure, incentives and costs have been
fine-tuned," she said at a seminar organized by the
Malaysian-Swedish Business Association here.
</P>
<P>
She said the question of track record was also important to see
beyond the current financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said Malaysia had several advantages with regards to
skills, capital and advanced manufacturing technology that could
upgrade manufacturing quality.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign investors are already setting up facilities in
Malaysia as their regional bases to optimize their competitive
advantages, she said.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said her International Trade and Industry Ministry
received 212 applications from January to April this year with
investments valued at 4,027 million ringgit (about 1,000 million
U.S. dollars), of which domestic applications amounted to 1,822.9
million ringgit (452.66 million U.S. dollars) while foreign
applications totaled 2,204.1 million ringgit (547.33 million U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
