<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 09:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Economy Remains Sluggish: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Despite some positive signs,
Israel's economy is still in slowdown, as suggested by reports on
stagnant construction and manufacturing sectors, two key
indicators for the overall performance of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Building-starts in the first quarter of this year plunged by 21
percent to 10,060 apartments compared with 12,680 in the same
period last year, according to figures of the Central Bureau of
Statistics carried by the Jerusalem Post Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The apartments completed in the first quarter fell to 11,970
units from last quarter's 17,660, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the Construction and Housing Ministry officials as
saying Monday that they predicted only half the land on sale for
housing construction this year would be sold.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Income Tax Commissioner Doron Levy said real estate
deals shrank by 30 percent in the first five months of this year
as against the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Manufacturers Association Monday
reported rising unemployment and declining production in a variety
of industries, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Among those worst hit are food, textiles, footwear, wood and
furniture, machinery production, rubber and plastics, Shuki
Abramovitz, head of the association's economics division said. But
he did not give specific figures.
</P>
<P>
All these reports came days after the Treasury expressed the
hope that recent macroeconomic indicators could suggest a possible
rebound in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production grew at an annualized 7-8 percent in
February and March, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
And there have been signs that the slowdown in investments in
factories and associated equipment is bottoming out.
</P>
<P>
The imports of investment goods rose 2 percent in April
following steady decline since September 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
