<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Privatize Public Transport Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Egypt plans to privatize its
inter-city passengers transport companies in July after their
conditions are fully adjusted, the English-language daily Egyptian
Gazette reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the plan Monday, Minister of Public Business Sector
Atef Ebeid, who is in charge of Egypt's privatization program,
played down fears of increasing coach fares after the
privatization.
</P>
<P>
"I believe it is not in the best interest of these companies to
raise their fares not only because of competition, but also that
they might drive passengers to use other means of transportations
such as trains," Ebeid was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added that his ministry will discuss the pricing issue with
the Ministry of Transport and Communications.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with officials at the
Holding Company for Transport Monday, Ebeid said privatizing
maritime transport companies should not be a cause for concern,
nor should the privative sector's competition be so intimidating.
</P>
<P>
"Public companies must not rely on their monopoly privileges,
but should improve their services to generate profits under a
competitive atmosphere," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister made it clear that maritime transport companies
are currently being modernized in preparation for privatization,
affirming that they will not be offered for sale unless the
chances of faltering are reduced to nil.
</P>
<P>
Since its privatization program was kicked off in 1996,
Egyptian government has sold majority stakes in scores of firms,
divested its interest in mobile telephone network and offered
infrastructure and utilities projects to private investors.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the government has offered 105 out of 314
state-owned companies for sale, at the speed of 10 companies every
three months, according to Mukhtar Khattab, advisor to the
minister of the public enterprise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
