<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 08:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beirut Voters Secure Sectarian Balance in Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The vote in Beirut in Lebanon's
first local elections in 35 years has secured a balanced
representation of Muslims and Christians in the city council, the
Daily Star newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to electoral results announced by Interior Minister
Michel Al-Murr Monday night, 12 Muslims and 12 Christians were
elected to the 24-member city council on Sunday in the third round
of the elections.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri hailed the results as "a
victory for national accord and co-existence," saying that
"national coexistence has proved the strongest."
</P>
<P>
Beirut has become a Sunni Muslim majority city over the years.
Before the elections were held here, Hariri called on his fellow
Sunni Muslim voters to elect Christians in a bid to maintain
religious harmony between the two sects.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's 1975-90 civil war was fought basically because of the
imbalances between the Muslims and Christians in the country.
</P>
<P>
The local elections were slated for the four consecutive
Sundays from May 24, during which members of 646 municipal
councils, 2,401 mayors and 7,662 representatives will be elected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
