<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Arms Producer in Australian Copter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's arms manufacturer
Denel is to work "exclusively" with British Aerospace (BAe) Australia
in a four-billion Rand (780-million-U.S. dollar) tender bid to replace
Australia's armed reconnaissance helicopters, local media said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
BAe Australia said Monday that deliveries for the contract of up to
40 helicopters for Australia's defense department will begin in 2003.
</P>
<P>
It said it had chosen Denel as a partner because it was impressed
with the Rooivalk helicopter, which had been offered to Malaysia and a
number of potential customers in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Denel's Chief Executive Seshi Chonco said the partnership was a tacit
recognition of the world class standards of the company's technology
and vindicated Denel's attempts aggressively to position the company
toward international strategic equity partnerships.
</P>
<P>
Tony Ennis, BAe Australia's marketing director, said the Rooivalk
was "highly capable" and "efficient" and would be an ideal solution to
the Australian army's requirements.
</P>
<P>
He said helicopters in this category were traditionally designed
for western European conditions. The Rooivalk, in contrast, had been
designed to operate in hot, dusty and coastal tropical conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
