<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Unveils New Member of Celeron Family </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Intel, the world's largest
computer chip-maker, introduced Monday the second member of its
Celeron family of central processor unit (CPU).
</P>
<P>
The new CPU chip, serving largely as the brain of personal
computers, or PCs, works at the frequency of 300 MHz, said the
company based in Santa Clara, California.
</P>
<P>
The 300 MHz Celeron is designed to meet the market segment for
PCs priced below 1,200 U.S. dollars, but Intel didn't give
suggested price was for the new chip.
</P>
<P>
The Celeron family, first unveiled last April with a 266 MHz
CPU chip, will replace Intel's latest Pentium series with
multimedia technology known as MMX.
</P>
<P>
Intel said PC makers such as Acer, Compaq, Dell,
Hewlett-Packard, IBM, Packard Bell, NEC and Sony are developing
systems based on the 300 MHz chip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
