<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two U.S. Big Banks Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Wells Fargo Co. and Norwest
Corp announced Monday a 34-billion-U.S. dollar merger that would
create a banking powerhouse stretching from California to Ohio.
</P>
<P>
Together, the Minneapolis-based Norwest and the San
Francisco-based Wells Fargo would be the nation's seventh-largest
merger overall and the third largest in the banking industry.
</P>
<P>
The combined bank, which will retain Wells Fargo's historic
name and headquarters, would have 191 billion dollars in assets.
</P>
<P>
It will have more branches, more mortgage loans and more
Internet customers than any others in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The new Wells Fargo, said experts, will operate in 21 states
with more than 90,000 employees, about 20 million customers and
more than 5,700 financial service outlets worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Experts expect the merger to save at least 650 million dollars
by the third year of combined operations while 2,130 positions
will be cut in both companies' current headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The merger follows several other huge banking deals.
</P>
<P>
Citicorp announced an 80-billion-dollar merger with Travelers
Group Inc. in April, which was quickly followed by the
60-billion-dollar merger of BankAmerican Corp. and NationsBank
Corp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
