<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection Improved In Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The environmental protection in
east China's Anhui Province is improving, according to the
provincial environmental protection bureau.
</P>
<P>
Almost all of Anhui's barren mountains have been planted with
forests and forest coverage is now 28.9 percent. Water quality has
improved in the Anhui section of the Yangtze River, reaching state
Category II standards, and in the Anhui section of the Huaihe
River it is at the same level as in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector has also made progress with pollution and
the province spent 1.85 billion yuan (230 million US dollars) on
pollution treatment from 1993 to 1997, for 2,758 projects. The
amount of industrial waste water, waste gas, and solid waste being
treated is 27, 2.7, and 8 percentage points higher than in 1992,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Companies along the Huaihe River reached standard waste water
discharge levels by the end of last year, and 1,009 wells and 94
water plants have been drilled or built to meet the demands of 1.8
million people.
</P>
<P>
The use of motor vehicle horns is prohibited in urban districts
of Anqing, Hefei, and Bengbu, and there are 359 square kilometers
with smoke controls, while the provincial capital, Hefei, is one
of the leading cities in China in environmental quality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
