<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airbus Aims to Increase Cooperation with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Airbus aims to have half of China's
airline market share, said Rolf Rue, Airbus Industry China's
general manager, in a recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Airbus is more confident of cooperation with China after the
new government took office last March, said Doug Yuguo, spokesman
for Airbus Industry China. The new government is intensifying
efforts to open wider to the outside world, he said, offering
greater opportunity for the company to develop business in China.
</P>
<P>
Airbus started its China operations in 1985, and has received
orders for 92 aircraft, 47 of which are now operational. In 1997
Airbus delivered 19 planes to China's airlines, an all-time
high. It predicts that by 2014 China will need 1,320 aircraft
valued at 100 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Airbus and China Air Equipment Export/Import Corp. set up the
Hua'Ou (China-Europe) Aviation Training and Supporting Center last
year to train Chinese pilots and other crew members.
</P>
<P>
Now, more than 20 multinational aviation equipment companies
have opened businesses in the center and established maintenance
services.
</P>
<P>
Airbus' cooperation with its Chinese counterparts is going
strong. Xi'an and Shenyang aircraft companies as well as Guiyang
Aviation Industrial Group, for example, are manufacturing hatch
doors, emergency exit doors, equipment and tools for ground
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
The Euro currency, which will soon be used in 11 European
countries, will make it easier to do business, Rue said.
</P>
<P>
Airbus Industry China was opened by multinational space
companies from France, Britain, Germany, and Spain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound in Tokyo, Boosted by Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rebounded Tuesday in
Tokyo with the key Nikkei index recovering the 15,500 line, led by
export-oriented issues benefiting from the U.S. dollar's surge to
the 141 Japanese yen level.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange rose 235.46 points, or 1.54 percent, from Monday's
close to end at 15,530.17.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, surged 10.32 points, or 0.36 percent, to
1,208.68.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the First Section went up to an estimated 310
million shares from Monday's 251 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan was the day's most heavily
traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Investors chased internationally competitive automobile and
electric appliance stocks after the dollar rose to 141.11 yen
early in the morning in Tokyo, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Stock prices were also supported by some investors who shifted
funds from bonds to stocks on fears of a further rise in bond
prices, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,336 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outnumbered losers 575 to 480, with 170 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
