<HEADLINE> Mandela Writes to South African Soccer Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The South African national
soccer team, Bafana Bafana, have received a special presidential
seal of encouragement ahead of their World Cup opening match
against France on Friday, The Star daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Coach Philippe Troussier and all 22 players have been sent
individual letters bearing touching words of inspiration from
Bafana Bafana's number one fan: President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will not be able to watch Bafana Bafana in action since
he is attending the Organization of African Unity's annual summit
in Burkina Faso and will then attend an European Union conference
in Cardiff, Wales.
</P>
<P>
"He wanted to give each player a feeling of his presence. He
wrote the letters himself last week," his spokesman Parks
Mankahlana said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The main letter was written on paper with a presidential letter
head, paper normally reserved for correspondence with heads of
states.
</P>
<P>
To captain Lucas Radebe Mandela wrote: "I am particularly proud
of you as captain, and of the South African soccer team."
</P>
<P>
He praised Troussier for the resilience the coach had shown "in
the face of unprecedented pressure."
</P>
<P>
"I am quite impressed with your training methods and the vision
you have outlined for the team," he wrote.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's words to Alfred Phiri were touching: "There is quite
a difference between Alexandra township where you were born and
Vichy, your camping site for the World Cup. You are representing
the aspirations of the youth, the majority of whom are striving to
pull themselves out of the most squalid condition."
</P>
<P>
The letters were sent to the South African embassy in France on
Friday and were due to be delivered Monday night by ambassador
Barbara Masekela, the paper said. 
</P>
