<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Central Bank Governor Confirms Stability Of Yuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The governor of the People's Bank
of China (PBOC), Dai Xianglong, told a seminar on the Asian
financial crisis here today that the yuan, China's currency, will
remain stable in spite of mounting pressure on the country's
exports caused by the recent devaluation of the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
Dai said that the sharp devaluation of the yen had a negative
impact on East Asian finances and economy, and put more pressure
on China's exports and said he hopes that the Japanese government
will take steps to stabilize the yen.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese government has had a responsible
attitude about the crisis and has offered whatever help it could.
</P>
<P>
China has provided over four billion U.S. dollars through the
International Monetary Fund and other channels to aid countries
hit by the crisis, he said, pointing out that this is a fairly big
sum for China, which is a large developing country with a heavy
foreign debt burden.
</P>
<P>
What is more important, he said, is that the Chinese government
has pledged not to devalue the yuan and to ensure 8 percent growth
this year, which will greatly benefit the Asian economy and
finance.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the East Asian currency crisis did not
have a direct impact on China, its consequences have increased and
East Asian economic adjustments and the devaluation of the yen
have had a negative impact on China's foreign trade and use of
foreign capital, and put greater pressure on China's economic
reforms and restructuring.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the currency crisis, China will continue to open
its financial sector to the outside world and more foreign banks
will be approved for doing business in yuan and more foreign
insurance companies will be allowed to enter China, while yuan and
foreign exchange loans will be increased for foreign-funded
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
