<HEADLINE> Northeast China Forest Coming Back A Decade After Conflagration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- About 95 percent of the forest that
was burned in the big fire ten years ago in the Da Xing'an Ling
Mountain Range in northeast China has grown back, according to the
local forestry bureau.
</P>
<P>
Da Xing'an Ling is one of China's important forests but was
heavily destroyed in the 1987 fire, when about 1.24 million
hectares of forest burned.
</P>
<P>
But an afforestation program helped speed up the restoration
process and the local forestry department paid great attention to
scientific management and new techniques that helped the nursery
stock increase 27-fold over methods used before the fire, and a
fire protection network was set up.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of restoration was completed at the end of 1996
and the second phase began in earnest last year, according to Zhu
Lieyun, deputy director of the local forestry bureau.
</P>
<P>
The landscape will be restored to the same level as before the
fire when the second phase is finished, he says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
