<HEADLINE> Israel's Major Banks Hit Record Profits in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Israel's five major banks earned
a total of 3.115 billion shekels (about 850 million U.S. dollars)
in profit last year, the Jerusalem Post daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This indicated a combined 43 percent increase for the five
banks compared with the previous year. The five banks are Bank
Hapoalim, Bank Leumi, Discount Bank of Israel, Bank United Mizrahi
and Bank First International.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Supervisor of Banks Zeev Abeles was quoted by the daily
as saying that an expansion of activity, rise in operating income
and decline in provisions for doubtful debts have secured the
profit increase.
</P>
<P>
In particular, he said, the increase in revenues from fees for
expanded use of bank services, greater activity in the capital
markets and fee hikes, has all contributed to the profit soar.
</P>
<P>
The banks succeeded in raising the average return on capital to
12 percent last year, the highest in recent years, compared to 8.8
percent in 1996 and 8.4 percent in 1995, he said. 
</P>
