<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child Labor Mars E. African Economy: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania might
have their plans of industrialization by 2020 frustrated with
large numbers of children engaged in intensive labor.
</P>
<P>
The three eastern African states are now leading the rest of
the world in proportional rate of working children, the East
African Standard newspaper Tuesday quoted latest World Bank data
on global trends of child labor and slavery as saying.
</P>
<P>
At least one out of three children aged between 10-14 years in
the region is in some form of economic activity, mostly in
agriculture, mining, fishing and domestic services, while many
others are in hawking, prostitution and garbage collection, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
Researchers Peter Fallon and Zafiris Tzannatos estimated that
there are about eight million working children in the three
states.
</P>
<P>
The child labor rate in the region stands at 33 percent, which
doubles the estimates in southeast Asian countries, they said.
</P>
<P>
Labor experts said that child labor in the three countries is
preventing children from accumulating human capital and skills
necessary for having higher incomes in life.
</P>
<P>
If the matter continues, it will eventually hold economic
growth, accelerate market failures and slow down the
industrialization, the experts warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
