<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Sees Bleak Future of Textile Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The future of Kenya's textile
industry looks bleak following the collapse of Kenya's only
remaining government-owned textile company whose unpaid bills
have run into millions of Shillings.
</P>
<P>
The fate of the Rift Valley Textile Mills (Rivatex) would have
been sealed last week, had the Kenyan government not moved to place
it in receivership, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
By putting the company in receivership, the government plans
to save the assets from being auctioned by creditors through
court action.
</P>
<P>
The decision was supported by the various debenture holders
who have a charge over the assets of the company based in
Eldoret, western Kenya.
</P>
<P>
According to Raphael Masinde who was appointed receiver
manager, the laws on receivership allow the 1,400 workers at the
factory to be re-hired under new terms.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Lucas Chepkitony, the immediate former managing
director of the company, said the problems facing local textile
firms could be traced to insufficient raw materials, lack of
markets and the flooding of the local market with sub-standard
imported goods.
</P>
<P>
Many Kenyan farmers had reduced their cotton acreage due to
low prices and insufficient supply of chemicals, he complained,
saying this had reduced the firm's production by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Rivatex depended on cotton from Uganda and Tanzania but there
was a shortage of the commodity in July and August in the two
countries caused by poor harvests after the drought which
directly affected the company," he said.
</P>
<P>
Many textile companies are also facing stiff competition due
to the liberalization of economy which caught many of them
unprepared, the press report commented.
</P>
<P>
The local market has been flooded by imported used clothes
which are sold in open air markets since the economic
liberalization process at the end of 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Other state-owned textile companies that have gone under in
recent years include Kisumu Cotton Mills, Mount Kenya Textile
Company and the Kenya Textile Mills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
