<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Province Tightening Liquor Sale Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province, in the
southern part of China, will tighten its controls on liquor sales
through promulgating a new regulation approved by the Provincial
People's Congress Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
The regulation allows provincial departments to tighten
controls on liquor manufacturers and to penalize companies or
individuals producing and selling bad alcohol.
</P>
<P>
In Shanxi Province, 26 people died after drinking bad alcohol
earlier this year, prompting the country to pay more attention to
standardizing liquor quality.
</P>
<P>
Many small simple distilleries and illegal sellers in the
province are the major sources of inferior liquor, according to
the Guangdong provincial government.
</P>
<P>
The regulation will take effect on August 1, and will require
provincial departments concerned to reinforce controls on alcohol
quality. 
</P>
