<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 07:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Charges on Nuclear Technology Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran has dismissed as a "baseless
claim by the Zionist (Israeli) circles" the allegation that Iran
had asked Pakistan to transfer its nuclear technology, the
official Islamic Republic News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi in New York Monday
said that Iran basically does not need such programs and has urged
India and Pakistan not to involve themselves in nuclear test
races.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi's remarks came after Israel called the nuclear
devices detonated by the Pakistanis late last month in response to
India's nuclear tests as "Islamic bombs."
</P>
<P>
Iran, among the Islamic countries, has hailed the Pakistani
nuclear explosions as Islamic world's deterrent Israel. The tests
in south Asia triggered serious concern about the proliferation of
nuclear technology in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said the real goal of Israeli accusations against
Iran was to justify its dangerous nuclear capability and its ever
growing stock of nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Israeli move was designed to
procrastinate supervision by the International Atomic Energy
Agency of its nuclear installations and the signing of the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT).
</P>
<P>
Iran believes that the strengthening of the NPT without any
discrimination to include nuclear powers and Israel, is the best
way to guarantee global peace, he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran has repeatedly stressed the need to eventually make South
Asia and the Middle East nuclear-free. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Chief Calls on Nigerians to Maintain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Commonwealth Secretary General
Emeka Anyaoku has appealed to Nigerians to remain calm and reach
a genuine consensus in choosing a successor to General Sani
Abacha who died early monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku, who sent a condolence message to the Abacha family,
Monday told the Zimbabwe News Agency that Nigerians should ensure
that peace prevailed in the oil-producing country of over 104
million people.
</P>
<P>
"I just heard the news of Abacha's death and I wish to convey
my condolences to the members of his family and I have no doubt
that all Nigerians would wish to ensure peace prevail," said
Anyaoku, who is in Harare en route to London from his first
official visit to Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, head of state and commander in chief of the Nigerian
armed forces, died at dawn Monday and was buried in his native
town of Kano in accordance with Moslem rites and tradition.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, who seized power in a bloodless coup in 1993, sent his
deputy to jail under a death sentence for plotting an alleged
coup last year.
</P>
<P>
Exiled opponents of the regime in London have already started
calling on Nigeria to hand the presidency over to Moshood Abiola,
the man widely believed to have won a 1993 presidential elections
annulled by the military.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Major-general Abudusalam Abubakar, Nigeria's
chief of defense staff, has been inaugurated as Nigeria's new
leader and the swearing-in took place Tuesday
morning in Nigerian capital.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, 54, died Monday, ending a four-year reign over
Africa's populous country. 
</P>
