<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Poor to Get 228 Million Dollars in Credit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Rural Advancement
Committee (BRAC) will disburse 10.5 billion taka (about 228
million U.S. dollars) under its micro-credit program for income
generating activities for the landless poor, a BRAC press release
available here Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
As the largest non-government organization in the country, the
BRAC disbursed 6.88 billion taka (about 150 million dollars) in
1997 under the micro-credit program.
</P>
<P>
The cumulated loans disbursed by the BRAC since it launched the
micro-credit program in 1996 has amounted to 22.77 billion taka
(about 495 million dollars) with a 98 percent repayment rate,
according to the release.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the savings with the BRAC of poor rural women
borrowers have gone up to 2 billion taka (about 43.5 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
At present, the BRAC has about 2 million borrowers, most of
whom are from landless poor households, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is one of the least developed countries, with over
80 percent of its 127-million population living in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government and non-government organizations
have undertaken a series of programs to alleviate poverty in the
rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
