<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PhDs Running Businesses in Southern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Some businesses that are run by
university grads with a doctorate or master's degree are doing
well in the city of Beihai in south China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
At one Sino-American pharmaceutical company, for example, 10 of
the 28 employees have PhDs, 7 of them having returned from studies
abroad. They are now working on gene-based medicines to treat
diseases that cause white blood cell problems.
</P>
<P>
Another of their finds is TPO, which produces blood platelets
and will soon be available on the market.
</P>
<P>
The Beihai Yinhe Electronics Co. Ltd. is another example. It
has 40 senior engineers and eight people with PhDs. The company
was established four years ago, and was listed just last April on
the Shenzhen Stock Exchange. On the first day of trading, it went
to 71 yuan per share in less than an hour, a record at the stock
exchange.
</P>
<P>
Superman brand gas heaters are produced by a company where 51.6
percent of the employees are university grads. The heaters have a
good reputation nationwide and a sizeable market share.
</P>
<P>
As the number of scholars becoming entrepreneurs increases,
hi-tech businesses have begun to contribute more to the city's
economic growth, so the city is going to work out more favorable
policies to attract even more intellectuals, according to Mayor
Jin Renshou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
