<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Build Botanical Garden in Desert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN June 9 (Xinhua) -- Several farmers in northwest China's
Shaanxi Province have spent three years building a botanical
garden in the Maowusu Desert to protect endangered plant species.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, 50 types of endangered plant species
had been brought to the garden, 13 of which were under state
Category II protection.
</P>
<P>
Xu Dengtang, Zhang Qingyuan, and Zhang Jingui started building
the garden on 200 hectares of ground in 1995, and its ten sections
now grow thousands of varieties of plants.
</P>
<P>
Among 389 types of endangered plant species in China, 50 have
already been brought here for cultivation. The garden has received
thousands of domestic and foreign visitors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
