<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improved Breeding Helping To Protect Chinese Yellow Croaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- New breeding methods for the greater
yellow croaker in Xiangshan Bay in China's Zhejiang province are
expected to save this fish from extinction.
</P>
<P>
More than three million greater yellow croakers have been
produced, making this the largest breeding center.
</P>
<P>
The greater yellow croaker has long been popular with the
Chinese for its taste, and in the 1970s, there were 200,000 to
300,000 tons of them harvested, 90 percent of that from the East
China Sea.
</P>
<P>
Then, overfishing in the 1980s sharply brought down their
numbers, so specialists in Zhejiang and Fujian provinces began to
do research on breeding methods in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, they succeeded in finding the proper methods and
extended the use to the East China Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Monks' Bowls Found In Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Archaeologists in the city of
Qingzhou, in China's Shandong Province, have unearthed a dozen
bowls used by monks at least 1,300 years ago at a local
construction site.
</P>
<P>
The city museum first discovered five ash pits during the
construction work and specialists then cleared them and found a
number of stone Buddhas, pots, and some glassware.
</P>
<P>
More than ten porcelain bowls were unearthed, one of which was
decorated with lotus designs left by monks of Longxing Temple,
which is quite near the construction site.
</P>
<P>
In a 2.6-meter-deep pit, several gilded Buddhas and broken
glassware were found.
</P>
<P>
Scholars have retrieved a great number of copper coins from the
five pits. The currency was quite popular during the Tang Dynasty
(618-907), they say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0272 </DOCNO>
