<HEADLINE> Ho Chi Minh City Relaxes Rules on World Cup Broadcasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Ho Chi Minh City has
withdrawn a regulation requiring bars, restaurants and other
public venues to obtain licences before broadcasting live World
Cup matches, according to local newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Saigon Giai Phong (Liberated Saigon) daily quoted the new
decision as saying: "Places showing live World Cup matches in
general are allowed to operate without completing procedures
for...licences unless they organise new places offering tickets
which could attract the masses."
</P>
<P>
The previous rule issued on May 30 required bars, hotels and
restaurants to apply for licences to show matches.
</P>
<P>
Southern Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon, is Vietnam's
largest city and the country's commercial hub. 
