<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Starts "Long March" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's seven-party opposition
alliance started a two-day "long march" to the country's
southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts Tuesday in protest against the
peace treaty the government signed with the tribals last December.
</P>
<P>
The major opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) started
the march from Paltan Maidan after a rally addressed by party
chief Begum Khaleda Zia, and the Jammat-e-Islami began from Ramna
Square, two hours later than scheduled because of the road
blockade erected by march opponents, according to media reports
here.
</P>
<P>
Party members and supporters from the northern and
south-western districts started arriving in the city Monday
afternoon by buses and other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
There were reports of clashes between supporters and opponents
of the march in different parts of the country, and the government
has reportedly taken precautionary measures to discourage people
from participation such as requisitioning heavy vehicles and
microbuses in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The opposition termed the long march as a "rehearsal to
safeguard the country's independence and sovereignty," while the
government described it as a program to "destabilize peace" in the
hill tracts, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The opposition has fiercely attacked the treaty since it was
signed in December 1997, accusing it of "violating the
Constitution," and "ignoring the interest of the nation." The
treaty was designed to end the decades-long armed conflict in the
Chittagong Hill Tracts.
</P>
<P>
"We also favor peace accord...but the one signed (between the
government and the tribals) contains some unconstitutional
provisions which require amendments," said Khaleda Zia, who is
also leader of the Opposition in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The seven-party alliance includes the BNP, the Jammat-e-Islami,
the Jatiya Party, the Democratic League, the National Democratic
Party, the Progressive Nationalist Party, and the Democratic
Nationalist Alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
