<HEADLINE> Thai Deputy PM: Govt Not to Intervene to Support Baht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The baht tumbled as the Japanese yen fell to a seven-year low
of below 140 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Since the fall of the baht was in line with the movement of
other regional currencies, the government will let market
mechanisms continue to work, the deputy prime minister was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed the yen would not fall too far below 140.
</P>
<P>
Intervention by the government to support the baht would affect
plans to lower interest rates, and would be harmful to businesses
in the long run, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, exporters are somewhat cheered by the depreciation
of the baht since it will strengthen the competitiveness of Thai
products.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit Nimla-or, president of the Thai Garment Manufacturers'
Association, said exporters were not worried about the weaker baht
as it would help support the country's exports.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that he believed the baht would become stable
at this level. 
