<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over Half of Indonesia's State Firms Unhealthy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A total of 53.8 percent of 160
state-owned companies in Indonesia were considered unhealthy, a
government official said.
</P>
<P>
The state companies booked a combined net profit of 11.83
trillion rupiah (1.18 billion U.S. dollars) last year, compared to
12.70 trillion rupiah (1.26 billion dollars) in 1996, State
Minister for the Empowerment of State Enterprises Tanri Abeng told
members of the House of Representatives Monday.
</P>
<P>
The profitability of the companies was very low when compared
to their combined assets of 461.643 trillion rupiah (46.1 billion
dollars) and their total equity of 123.42 trillion rupiah (12.3
billion dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
"Although total assets grew by 2.7 percent (in 1997), the
increase wasn't accompanied by an improved ability to make a
profit," he added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has 176 state-owned companies, but only 160 come
under the control of Tanri's office.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Tanri had appointed U.S.-based consultancy
firm Booz, Allen and Hamilton to lead the process of restructuring
the ailing state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
The company, together with the World Bank, the Asian
Development Bank and several of the country's leading management
institutions, will submit a restructuring blueprint in September,
including a future privatization agenda.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government plans to privatize 12 state-owned
companies in the 1998-99 fiscal year ending March 31, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
