<HEADLINE> Heavy Interest Delays Thai Auction of Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Extensive interest shown by both
domestic and international investors has forced Thailand's
Financial Restructuring Authority (FRA) to delay by one week the
auction of part of the core assets of 56 closed finance companies.
</P>
<P>
The assets to be auctioned are 300,000 hire-purchase loans
worth 46 billion baht (1.07 billion U.S. dollars), the Bangkok
Post said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The auction, the first of core financial assets of the 56
closed companies, was originally scheduled for June 18, but had to
be postponed to June 25 to give investors more time to study the
information on the assets up for sale, the newspaper quoted FRA
Chairman Amaret Sila-on as saying.
</P>
<P>
For the past three weeks, representatives from local and
foreign financial institutions have been pouring over
documentation and data on the hire-purchase loans, Amaret said.
</P>
<P>
The FRA has to set up five data rooms, opening 24 hours a day,
where investors could review information representing a 10 percent
random sample of the entire loan portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Even though, there is insufficient time to accommodate
investors' demand for access, the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that only serious investors participated, the FRA
charged a 200,000 baht (4,650 dollars) non-refundable
administration fee for access to the data room, and a refundable
deposit of 10 billion baht (232.6 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Binding bids for the seven lots up for sale, together with a 2
percent bid deposit, must be submitted by June 25. The FRA will
evaluate bids and sign contracts within seven days.
</P>
<P>
After the hire-purchase loans are auctioned, the FRA will begin
sales of mortgage loans.
</P>
<P>
Amaret said FRA'a main target for the asset auctions is
investors in the United States and Europe, where the FRA will
begin roadshows starting in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
