<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Asia: From Financial Crisis to Recession? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- As the Asian financial crisis has
entered its 11 months, more countries in the region are facing the
danger of sliding into recession before their hopes for a quick
recovery began to fade.
</P>
<P>
Economists have described as "worse than expected" the region's
performance in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, Malaysia's economy shrank 1.8
percent in the first three months of this year, while the
Philippines' gross domestic product growth slowed down to a
lower-than-expected 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, manufacturing production fell 21 percent in March
from a year earlier. Its exports fell 3.5 percent in March from a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Although Singapore registered a strong growth of 5.6 percent in
the first quarter, economists predicted that its economy will slow
down with the deepening of the economic gloom in Malaysia and
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the first quarter performance might bar a
strong rebound in the second quarter, and the full-year figures
will not look better.
</P>
<P>
Some economists predicted that Malaysia, Singapore and Japan
might join Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea in the 1998
recession line-up.
</P>
<P>
As Asian countries try their best to revive economic growth,
the health of the Japanese economy is obviously affecting the
region's recovery process.
</P>
<P>
For more than a decade, Japan had been the key driver for
Asia's economies, feeding the satellite industrial machine with
infrastructure, expertise and credit. It was the Japanese yen that
built Asia's industrial machines, pushing Asia's investment-led
economies toward high growth rates that attracted billions of
dollars to the region.
</P>
<P>
But those days are over, as the health of the Japanese economy
is deteriorating with its currency depreciating. In the early
Tuesday morning trading, the Japanese yen reached a new low of 141
to the U.S. dollar, the lowest in seven years.
</P>
<P>
Even if the Japanese government's stimulus package of tax cuts
and public spending would push the annual growth above zero, the
fate of the yen is uncertain, economists said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts expressed their fears that a steady slide in the
Japanese yen against the greenback risks catapulting Asia into
another round of currency depreciation.
</P>
<P>
Further weakness of Asian currencies, some of which have
depreciated over 50 to 80 percent since last July, would no doubt
delay the region's recovery prospects and expose some of the
economies to depression.
</P>
<P>
To prevent further depreciation of their currencies, Asian
economies would have to keep their interest rates high. However,
high interest rates and a drying up of credit in turn could mean
that more companies are unable to finance their business and repay
their debts. More closures of companies and banks would follow.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, with far less money coming into the region than being
pulled out, the burden of reviving growth falls on the Asian
countries' own external finances.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter, imports into Thailand, Indonesia, the
Philippines and South Korea fell by about 30 percent from a year
ago. Since most of these countries' exports rely heavily on
imported materials and components, the declines indicate that the
long-awaited export boom that would lead to a recovery remains a
distant hope.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, export growth slowed sharply to 9.8 percent
in April from a year earlier, the lowest year-on-year increase in
nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
All these factors point to gloomy prospects for the Asian
economies which might possibly lead to recession later this year,
experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0291 </DOCNO>
