<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Modern Agriculture For Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- More Chinese farmers are changing
their traditional methods of farming and turn to science and
technology instead.
</P>
<P>
In Henan Province, central China, many farmers are finding that
the old methods just don't work as well as before. The lack of
access to market information cost them dearly in marketing their
products, according to Gao Xi, who invented a way to plant a
mixture of wheat, corn, and vegetables and get 6 times the output
on a piece of land each year.
</P>
<P>
Modern agriculture is focusing on commercialization, and badly
needs scientific research, according to Dr. Sun Baozhong, of the
Chinese Academy of Agricultural Science, who helped bring the idea
of modern agriculture to farmers.
</P>
<P>
Sun and his team got farmers to sign contracts to take care of
the cattle for 200,000 yuan annually and taught them how to raise
cattle at lower cost, and how to sell the beef at a higher price.
</P>
<P>
In the past, it was natural for farmers to rely heavily on
experience in their farm work, but most are now turning to
technology and market knowledge for better harvests, which is
greatly helping agricultural development, keeping costs down, and
profits up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Opposed to Military Role in Anti-Drug Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela will submit a proposal to
the United Nations General Assembly insisting on police rather
than military intervention in anti-drug efforts.
</P>
<P>
The proposal will be submitted by Carlos Tablante, the
Venezuelan minister of state and president of the National
Anti-Drug Commission.
</P>
<P>
The three-day U.N. General Assembly special session opened in
New York on Monday and it has been called to adopt a global
strategy on combating drugs.
</P>
<P>
Tablante said he did not intend to start a conflict with the
United States, but he considered the strategies oriented to a
multi-national military alliance ignored the integral nature of
the worldwide drug problem.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that his country supports the creation of a
multi-national criminal investigation police and the establishment
of a supra-national criminal court.
</P>
<P>
Tablante also said he will propose other topics to be discussed
at the three-day meeting such as "precursory chemicals."
</P>
<P>
"The First-World countries should assume their social
responsibility without pretending that their precursory chemicals
move into the international market under nobody's control," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Other topics he mentioned included money laundering and
narcotic and psychotropic abuse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
