<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Stealth Fighters Back from Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States has withdrawn
12 F-117a stealth fighters which were deployed in Kuwait last
November in a military build-up against Iraq over the weapons
inspection crisis.
</P>
<P>
The stealth fighters were flown home to Holloman Air Force Base
in New Mexico last Saturday and Sunday, said Pentagon spokesman
Marine Corps Major Bryan Salas.
</P>
<P>
The United States had already pulled back eight B-52 bombers
and an aircraft carrier from the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. reduction of its military presence was made after the
Clinton administration decided that tension in the region had
subsided after Iraq's compliance with U.N. resolutions on weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen, however, said late last month
that the reduction did not "represent a change in our willingness,
our ability, to carry out any mission in the region."
</P>
<P>
"There's a great deal of firepower remaining and a lot of
prepositioned equipment and the ability to augment the size of
that force within about 48 hours," he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned warplanes that have been flown home would remain on
the alert in the United States and could be returned to the area
in a new emergency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
