<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Import Activities Drop Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's import activities had
dropped by more than 80 percent over the last few months, due to
the refusal of most Indonesian letters of credit by foreign banks,
press reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Since the regional monetary crisis hit Indonesia and shook the
banking sector last July, most letters of credit issued by local
banks have been turned down by overseas banks, according to
Amirudin Saud, chairman of the Indonesian Importers Association.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Amirudin said, most local banks, which are suffering
from a liquidity crisis, require importers to pay up-front the
full amount of the letters of credit they want to open.
</P>
<P>
Latest official data showed total imports declined by 35.2
percent in March to 2.37 billion dollars compared to those in the
same month of last year.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter of this year, the country's imports
reached 7.2 billion dollars. Last year, Indonesia's imports
totaled 41.67 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the remaining import activities now are based on the
trust built from long-term relationships between buyers and their
foreign partners, which allow transactions without letters of
credit," Amirudin said.
</P>
<P>
Commodities which are still being imported include chemical
materials, textiles and medicines.
</P>
<P>
Importers unable to continue their activities have simply
deposited their funds at local banks to earn high interests for
meeting a payroll of their workers, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
