<HEADLINE> Latin-American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs in Latin American countries in the past few
days:
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Heavy rains and strong winds destroyed a total
of 300,000 banana plants last Saturday in Panama's Atlantic
province of Bocas de Toro.
</P>
<P>
The country's banana exports are expected to drop by 5-8
percent due to the disaster, General Manager of Panama's Banana
Company Adrian Guzman said.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Costa Rican Oil Refinery (RECOPE) has spent 45
million U.S. dollars on import of modern petroleum refinery
equipment.
</P>
<P>
With the installation of these equipment, the RECOPE will be
able to increase its petroleum production to 25,000 barrels per
day from 15,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the company has to import 18,000 barrels of refined
oil per day to satisfy its national demand which stands at 33,000
barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico will import 15 million tons of grains
this year, local journal El Financiero reported.
</P>
<P>
Cereal production is expected to fall by 40-50 percent due to a
serious drought in the country.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina will prohibit the manufacture and
import of diesel-powered automobiles by the year 2000, Secretary
of Industry, Commerce and Mining Alieto Guadagni announced.
</P>
<P>
But the ban does not include public transportation and freight
vehicles, he added.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was due to the enormous price differences
between gasoline and diesel oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
