<HEADLINE> U.S. Sets Conditions for Improving Ties with Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
reacted to the death of Nigeria's leader Sani Abacha by saying
that it linked its improvement of relations between the two
countries to Nigeria's genuine transition to civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
"A genuine transition to civilian rule would enable the U.S.
to strengthen and deepen its ties to Nigeria, to the mutual
benefit of both our nations," State Department spokesman James
Rubin said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
"Our hope is that Nigeria's new leadership will continue and
make credible the transition program currently in place,
culminating in inauguration of a freely elected civilian
government on October 1," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, 54, who died of a heart attack on Monday, came to power
in 1993 after the military canceled a presidential election in
mid-count.
</P>
<P>
he had been expected to transform himself into an elected
civilian president in a election planned for August 1.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said in New York that the
U.S. government "is interested in seeing a freely and
democratically elected civilian government" after Abacha's death.
</P>
</TEXT>
