<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's One-Child Policy Helping The Life Insurance Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- According to an insurance
salesperson in China's Henan Province, the most populous province
in China, "It's easier to talk a family into buying children's
insurance than any other insurance policy."
</P>
<P>
He learned this interesting fact from his work at the Henan
branch of the People's Insurance Company of China (PICC), one of
China's leading life insurance companies, and that parents are
likely to spend more on their children than on themselves. This is
because most families now only have one child.
</P>
<P>
A young couple, for example, bought their baby girl life
insurance and marriage insurance (based on a legal marriage age of
20 for girls and 22 for boys), which cost them more than 4,000
yuan annually, compared to the two retirement policies they spent
1,000 yuan a year on for themselves.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of the 18 million students in Henan, from
primary school to university, are covered by accident insurance
from PICC's Henan branch.
</P>
<P>
Life insurance accounts for 52.3 percent of the company's
premiums of 1.7 billion yuan in 1997, an unprecedented 106 percent
increase from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the brisk life insurance business, however,
medical insurance is far from popular. PICC's Henan branch's
medical insurance accounted for only 2 policies per 1,000 last
year, and 48 million yuan in premiums.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jinwei, the director of the company's medical insurance
department, explains that its medical insurance lacks
variety. However, a recent company poll also showed that 27.25
percent of the surveyed hope to have medical insurance. It shows
that there is a huge market potential for us to tap, Zhang added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
