<HEADLINE> Multi-Country Meeting on HIV/AIDS Held in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A multi-country meeting on HIV/AIDS
is being held here to exchange views on efforts to contain the
spread of the diseases resulting from drug abuse and sexual
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, which began Monday, is organized by the
UNAIDS and the Asia and Pacific Inter-Country Team (APICT).
</P>
<P>
Discussions on cooperation in HIV/AIDS prevention in the border
areas, participated by health officials from China, Myanmar and
Thailand as well as representatives of the United Nations
agencies, are underway, The New Light of Myanmar newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Myanmar Minister of Health Major-General Ket
Sein as saying that the country has laid down special programs to
protect the inhabitants in the border areas from AIDS since the
disease spread across border in mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
Public education was also carried out to reach grass-root level
and community-based healthcare services were provided in
cooperation with non-governmental organizations inside and outside
the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar formed the National AIDS Committee in 1989.
</P>
<P>
According to official data, there were 17,846 HIV positives and
2,337 AIDS cases in Myanmar as of the end of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
