<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's GDP Up 4.6 Percent in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's gross domestic product
(GDP) registered a 4.6 percent increase in the 1997-98 fiscal year
ended March, according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The productive sector rose by 4.3 percent, the services sector
by 7.4 percent and the trade sector by 3.2 percent respectively as
compared with the 1996-97 fiscal year, said a current official
report of Myanmar's financial, economic and social conditions
issued by the Ministry of National Planning and Economic
Development.
</P>
<P>
Of the productive sector, agriculture, which is the mainstay of
the country's economy accounting for 35 percent of the total GDP,
increased by 2.9 percent, lower than the set target of 6.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the low GDP growth of 4.6 percent, which
is lower than the set target of 6.4 percent, to flash floods and
drought during the fiscal year in some areas which resulted in
less production of main crops, less production of
agriculture-related manufacturing sector and drop in trade volume.
</P>
<P>
The value of exports in the fiscal year amounted to about one
billion U.S. dollars, while the imports stood at 2.2 billion
dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The 1997-98 fiscal year was the second year of Myanmar's
current Five-Year Plan (1996-97 to 2000-01), the average annual
growth target of which was set at 6 percent. The first year of the
plan, which is the 1996-97, achieved a 5.8 percent growth in GDP.
</P>
<P>
The last Four-Year Plan (1992-93 to 1995-96) saw an average
annual growth rate of 7.3 percent compared with the original
target of 5.6 percent, mainly due to the growth achieved by the
agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
In the 1998-99 fiscal year which began in April, the country's
GDP is set to increase at 6.2 percent, of which agriculture is set
to rise at 5 percent, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
