<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Private Sector Owes 29b U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian private sector's foreign
debt due this fiscal year ending March 31, 1999 totals 29.2
billion U.S. dollars, a government official was quoted by press
reports Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's external corporate debt stood at 20 billion U.S.
dollars and the non-trade liabilities of commercial banks at 9.2
billion U.S. dollars, Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance
and Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita told reporters after meeting
President B.J. Habibie here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ginanjar, along with Director General of Financial Institutions
Glenn Yusuf, Bank Indonesia Director Dono Iskandar and Indonesian
debt settlement team chairman Radius Prawiro, met with Habibie to
report about an agreement with creditors to restructure the
country's mounting private foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and its creditor banks agreed in Frankfurt, Germany,
last week on a program relating to private corporate debt,
external credits to the Indonesian banking system and trade
finance.
</P>
<P>
"Hence, last week's agreement to reschedule the foreign debts
for up to eight years, including three years of grace period,
would be quite a relief," Ginandjar said.
</P>
<P>
"If we (our companies) have to repay entirely these 30 billion
U.S. dollars debts, it would be quite a pressure on our balance of
payments because that amount is more than twice as large as our
foreign exchange reserves," he added.
</P>
<P>
Dono predicted that the rupiah would start to strengthen when
the program becomes operational on August 1 as demand for U.S.
dollars should drop.
</P>
<P>
"The current (dollars-rupiah) exchange rate is still too high
because demand for dollars and other foreign exchange are still
increasing due to our huge debts," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah slid against the U.S. dollar again Monday, closing
at 11,750 against the greenback, compared to Friday's close of
11,500. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
