<HEADLINE> Hincapie Wins U.S. Pro Cycling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- George Hincapie won the $30,000
U.S. professional cycling championship, one of the richest one-day
road races in the world in Philadelphia today.
</P>
<P>
"All I can say that is if anyone has anything to say, let them
say it now," said Hincapie, 24, who won back the winner's jersey
snatched from him a year ago due to a last-lap penalty.
</P>
<P>
Hincapie and his four teammates from the U.S. postal cycling
team, including former world champion Lance Armstrong, controlled
the last third of the 156-mile race and built up a more than
three-minute gap.
</P>
<P>
The group finished the course in 6 hours, 6 minutes and 25
seconds.
</P>
<P>
"Lance told me that I could win this race, so I just made my
break through," said the winner.
</P>
<P>
Hincapie also won the Solidarity Cup, a combination of races in
Poland and America. The American, who disqualified last year
because he moentarily drafted a team car in the last lap, beat
Italian Massilimilano Mori by a wheel's length. Tomas Konecny of
the Czech Repulic wound up third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
