<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Passes 140 yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose past 140
Japanese yen Monday for the first time in seven years as investors
again turned to U.S. assets and moved away from ever-weakening yen.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also rose against the Deutsche mark and other major
currencies, but dealers focused their attention on dollar-yen
trading.
</P>
<P>
At the closing in New York, the dollar was quoted at 140.71
yen, up from 139.75 yen late Friday. The dollar once rose to
140.75 yen, a level not seen since June 1991.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was changing hands at 1.7794 marks in New York, up
from 1.7745 Friday.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6337 dollars, down from
1.6353 dollars. 
</P>
