<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Well-preserved Ancient Kiln Discovered In Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A 4,000-year-old kiln has been
unearthed at Yuanqu County in north China's Shanxi Province with a
number of pieces of pottery, the third to be found.
</P>
<P>
Scholars say that this kiln is the best-preserved one of that
period. It is 3 meters tall and has three parts: the fire chamber,
a tunnel, and a firing room.
</P>
<P>
Below the fire chamber, scholars found an air vent and some mud
blocks serving as baffles, revealing what people of the New Stone
Age knew about controlling the fire in pottery making.
</P>
<P>
A work ground was found nearby, with a small road leading to
the kiln, and some footprints on the road can still be seen
clearly, the scholars report, explaining that they helped
craftsmen see where to walk to keep from slipping while carrying
the pottery.
</P>
<P>
There were many pots, tripods, and cauldrons inside the kiln,
decorated with quite simple designs.
</P>
<P>
Scholars say the three kilns give a better picture of pottery
making in prehistoric times and provide materials with which to
study New Stone Age culture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0330 </DOCNO>
