<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surface Subsidence In Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Ten sites in a 24-square-kilometer
area near the city of Ruijin along the banks of the Shazhou River
in China's Jiangxi Province have sunk since last November, causing
a wall to collapse and cracks to appear in at least 30 buildings.
</P>
<P>
Ruijin was one of China's revolutionary bases in the early
1930s, and many old buildings in the city are under state
protection as cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Some cracks in the buildings are 10 cm. wide, putting buildings
and houses in danger of collapsing, according to the local geology
department.
</P>
<P>
They say the subsidence is the result of excessive use of
underground water for agriculture and aquaculture. The local
government has taken steps to control the use of subsurface water
and is doing further studies of the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0338 </DOCNO>
