<HEADLINE> Peru Calls for Contributions to Its Anti-Drug Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Peru has called on
international donors to earmark part of debt service as anti-drug
funds for the eradication of drug crops.
</P>
<P>
For that purpose, Peru is inviting friendly countries to attend
a donors roundtable meeting in October, President Alberto Fujimori
told the U.N. special session on drugs here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be held under the auspices of the
Inter-American Development Bank and the Inter-American Commission
for Drug Abuse Control, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the drug crop producing countries are restricted by
debt service commitments entailed by high-level external debts.
</P>
<P>
"This is why we believe that developed countries should make
every effort to support us and to avoid breakdowns in the process
that will generate more frustration and poverty and recreate the
conditions for a revival of drug trafficking," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori said Peru's acreage under illicit coca has been
reduced from 120,000 hectares in 1990 to 60,000 hectares now and
that there is a drop in the number of rural families tied to the
coca economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
