<HEADLINE> 16 Killed in Philippine Army, Rebels Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen Muslim rebels and three
Philippine soldiers had been killed in intense fighting over the
weekend in a southern Philippine province, the Philippine Daily
Inquirer reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a military report, the newspaper said soldiers backed by
helicopter gunships overran late Friday a remote jungle camp of
the separatist Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), triggering
fighting that lasted until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Col. Reynaldo Alcasid, head of the Army brigade that launched
the operation, was quoted as saying the raid on Camp Salman in
Tungawan town, southern Zamboanga del Sur, was in retaliation for
crimes allegedly perpetrated by splinter MILF members.
</P>
<P>
"It was our response to a string of highway robberies,
extortion, cattle rustling and intimidation on civilians blamed on
these breakaway factions," Alcasid said.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway group from the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF) which signed a peace treaty with the
government in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
The group refused to be included in the peace treaty but have
been negotiating with the government since January 1997.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which has fought for a separate Islamic state in
Mindanao, is currently the strongest anti-government force in the
country, with an estimated membership of more than 12,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
