<HEADLINE> Eastern Chinese Farmers Getting Rid Of Sickles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Because of the greater mechanization,
of agriculture, 80 percent of the farmers in China's Anhui
Province will no longer be using sickles, the traditionally
indispensable tool used in harvesting wheat.
</P>
<P>
Anhui has over 2 million hectares of wheat to harvest this
summer, 1.6 million hectares of which is expected to be done by
machine.
</P>
<P>
The province has one of the highest mechanization levels in
China, and large harvesters from rice-growing areas in other
provinces are in Anhui to help with the harvest.
</P>
<P>
This method can save farmers from buying every type of
machinery, much of which can lay idle in the off season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
