<HEADLINE> U.S. Woman Forwar Honored by FIFA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. women's national team
forward Michelle Akers was awared FIFA's order of merit Sunday as
the FIFA Congress opened in Pairs.
</P>
<P>
Akers, 32, was honored as "an outstanding representative of
women's football." She has been a member of the U.S. women's team
since 1985 and has scored nearly 100 goals in international play.
</P>
<P>
She helped the United States won the inaugural Women's World
Cup in 1991, and the gold medal in the inaugural women's Olympic
soccer competition in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Also receiving the order of merit were Germany's Gerd Muller,
described as "one of the dealiest goal-poachers in football
history," Brazilian goalkeeper Gilmar, "the last line of defense
where all the sportlight was on the forwards," and South Africa
President Nelson Mandela, for his role in reintegarating his
country into world soccer after an absence from 1976 to 1992
because of apartheid policies. 
</P>
