<HEADLINE> Kim Urges U.S. to Ease Sanctions on DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 8 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung Monday urged the United States to ease its sanctions
against the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and to
reduce tension on the divided Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"It would be desirable for the United States to ease its
economic sanctions on North Korea," Kim said at a luncheon hosted
by the Council on Foreign Relations in New York.
</P>
<P>
Kim arrived in New York last Saturday en route to Washington
for his first state visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Since his inauguration in February, Kim has pursued a policy of
engagement with DPRK, lifting restrictions to allow expanded
business cooperation and cultural exchanges between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan at
U.N. headquarters in New York, Kim also said that his government
advocated gradual improvement of relations with DPRK, a South
Korean spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Now is the right time to improve relations between North and
South Korea," Kim told Annan.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, Kim met with some Wall Street investors for
discussion on financial situations in South Korea before going to
Washington for talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton. 
</P>
