<HEADLINE> Columbian President Tells of Drugs Scourge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Columbian President Ernesto
Samper Pizano said here on Monday that the scourge of drugs can
only be compared to "one of the seven Biblical plagues".
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the U.N. special session on drugs, he said drugs
have in the past 20 years brought sufferings to his countrymen by
perturbing once a peaceful country.
</P>
<P>
"The cursed drug money penetrated the economy, suddenly took
over honest business, contaminated politics and corrupted
values," he said.
</P>
<P>
"More than 3,000 policemen fell victim to terrorism", he said,
adding that "drug money became a source for funding for the
various forms of violence that we are fighting against today".
</P>
<P>
He said Columbia has to spend one billion U.S. dollars a year
to combat drug trafficking, a sum equivalent to 21 percent of the
cost to provide education for Columbian children.
</P>
<P>
Summing up his country's success in the fight, he said Columbia
has in recent years eradicated 60 percent out of the total coca
crops eradicated in the world and 36 percent out of the poppy
crops eradicated worldwide.
</P>
<P>
"We dismantled the two largest drug cartels, Medellin and Cali,
and we have more than 9,000 drug traffickers in prison," he added.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of international cooperation, the
President said only by actively working against all the links in
the chain of production, distribution and use of narcotics will
the international community be able to think of a definitive way
out of the drug problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
