<HEADLINE> Germany, Russia Hold First High-Level Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl started here Monday the first
high-level government consultations between the two countries in a
bid to forge closer ties and improve cooperation.
</P>
<P>
With the start of the new mechanism of contact between Bonn and
Moscow, which goes along the lines of the regular high-level
consultations Germany holds with some other European countries,
German officials have spoken of "a special quality" of the
German-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also told reporters upon his arrival in Bonn Monday
afternoon that the bilateral consultations, which will be held
once a year in the future, indicated that the Russian-German
cooperation "has reached a higher level".
</P>
<P>
During the first round of talks held Monday evening between
Yeltsin and Kohl, the two leaders had discussed a wide range of
issues including the political situation in Russia, bilateral
economic cooperation, the battle against organized crime as well
as the Kosovo conflict, a German government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders' positions on international issues were "very
close", Yeltsin's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
On the Kosovo conflict, Yeltsin stressed that Kosovo was an
inseparable part of Yugoslavia. He also said that political
pressure should be put on Belgrade and Kosovo-Albanian leaders in
order to restart their dialogue as soon as possible, the Russian
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman declined to comment on the question of
whether Russia would support a possible NATO military intervention
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel stressed on Sunday that in
case of a Western intervention in the Kosovo conflict, Russia must
also be involved.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the talks, the two countries on Monday also
signed two agreements on nuclear cooperation.
</P>
<P>
One of the accord foresaw Russian deliveries of enriched
uraniam to a German nuclear research reactor in Munich. A second
agreement would serve to encourage deliveries of German
technologies to improve the security level of Russian nuclear
power plants, German officials said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the two sides will hold the formal round of the
talks with the participation of government ministers including
foreign, finance and defense ministers.
</P>
<P>
Kohl and Yeltsin are due to hold a joint press conference after
the meetings on Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
