<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Urged Not to Ban Foreign Satellite Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Aerospace Industries
Association has urged Congress here Monday not to ban U.S. satellite
launch atop Chinese rockets, warning that any policy change would
hurt the U.S. national interests.
</P>
<P>
AIA President Don Fuqua told a press conference that the issue
of Chinese launches of U.S. commercial satellites involves many
complex, technical, policy and political issues. "unfortunately,
the actions of the House were the result of a number of different
issues becoming entangled and confused."
</P>
<P>
On May 22, the House of Representatives passed several
amendments to the House Defense Authorization Bill, that if
accepted by the Senate, will have widespread implications for the
aerospace industry, U.S. national interest, and the American
public.
</P>
<P>
The House endorsed the bill amid speculations that the decision
to allow U.S. satellites to be launched atop Chinese rockets might
be influenced by political contributions and that sensitive
technology might be leaked. The House and the Senate have set up
task force to investigate the allegations.
</P>
<P>
"We urge restraint by Congress until the results of its own
reviews are complete. We believe that the existing launch policy
is sound. The policy benefits not only the industry and consumers,
but the nation," said Fuqua, who joined the AIA ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. aerospace industries fear that the prohibition on
Chinese launches of U.S. satellites would turn that market over to
their French, Italian, and German competitors as well as other
customers who desire Chinese launches for economic or political
reasons.
</P>
<P>
Given that most available launch capability for the next three
years is already booked, lack of access to Chinese launchers would
also disrupt launch plans of U.S. communications companies,
resulting in financial losses.
</P>
<P>
"Our national interest is served by engagement with China,"
asserted Fuqua, who wrote to President Bill Clinton early this
month to express support to his China policy.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. aerospace industry, one of the leading U.S. exporters
to China, is appreciative of your Administration's decision to
renew China's Most Favored Nation (MFN) trade status for another
year. The members of the Aerospace Industries Association strongly
support your policy of engagement with the Chinese," he wrote in
his letter dated June 3.
</P>
<P>
Fuqua expressed the hope that the current controversy
concerning Chinese launches of American satellites will not affect
the U.S. government's policy of engagement.
</P>
<P>
He told President Clinton that U.S. aerospace trade with China
in 1997 rose to 2.3 billion U.S. dollars from 1.7 billion dollars
in 1996, accounting for 17.6 percent of all U.S. exports to China.
</P>
<P>
U.S. satellite manufacturers have ordered six Long March
launches in 1997, while China's Long March is expected to service
11 percent of the space launch market during 1997-2006.
</P>
<P>
According to an AIA press release, as of March 1997, 25 Long
March launches have been tentatively booked through 2004. Over the
next decade, Euroconsult estimates the space launch market will
grow 86 percent, while the Teal Group forecasts 1,697 satellites
will be launched between 1998-2007.
</P>
<P>
The widespread attention on Chinese launches of U.S. satellites
will continue over the following weeks as hearings are held, the
annual MFN debate unfolds, the President visits China, political
connections are examined, and the nuclear balance of power in Asia
is tested, Fuqua predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0354 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Storage Management Software Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, June 8 (Xinhua) -- As companies look for more ways to
handle storage management internally, the worldwide storage management
software market is expected to reach 4.8 billion U.S. dollars by 2002.
</P>
<P>
The software revenue in 1997 surpassed 2 billion dollars, according
to Dataquest, a California-based market analysis firm.
</P>
<P>
The market is being driven by three key segments: core, backup and
storage resource management.
</P>
<P>
Core storage management, namely file systems, volume management and
physical replication, involves products that provide basic
organization functions and ensure data integrity and availability by
offering fast failure recovery and data redundancy. Core product
vendor revenue reached 478.4 million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Backup products, which provide backup, restore, archive and
hierarchical storage management tools, reached 1.33 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Products of storage resource management, which manage properties of
physical and logical storage resources such as media health,
availability, space loading, performance connectivity and utilization,
provided 210 million dollars in revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980609.0355 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
