<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances Eco-Project in East Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has disbursed 3.2
million U.S.Dollars for the conservation of eco-projects across
the border areas of Uganda, Kenya, Sudan and Tanzania for the
coming five years.
</P>
<P>
Robert Nabanyumya, the National Project Manager, was quoted by
Monday's Monitor Daily as saying that the money is part of an
east African regional cross-border bio-diversity project and it
has been channelled through the global environment facility and
United Nations development program.
</P>
<P>
He said:''Implementation of the project will be by the
National Environment Management Authority where this core
project-staff unit will be located.''
</P>
<P>
''The project covers an expanse stretching from Sango Bay in
Rakai District into northern Tanzania drylands, to western
Kenya,'' Nabanyumya added.
</P>
<P>
The main project components are to be executed by the U.N.
Food and Agriculture Organization and governments of countries
conerned. 
