<HEADLINE> Five Killed in South African Ship Wreck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Five people drowned and
another 12 were feared dead after a South African-owned fishing
vessel sank off the Argentinian coast Saturday, South Africa's
Ambassador to Argentina said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The nationalities of the deceased had not yet been
established, Ambassador Aubrey Nkomo was quoted by South African
Press Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Luship, a Namibian-registered vessel, sank in rough seas
about 300 km from South Georgia Island after apparently being
struck by a big wave, Nkomo said.
</P>
<P>
The 38 crew members aboard the ship included South Africans,
Namibians and Irish, he said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one people were rescued later by a Chilean vessel, the
Isla Camila, the first to answer the 360-ton Luship's distress
call.
</P>
<P>
By Monday afternoon, five ships and an airplane from the
British Royal Air Force were still looking for survivors.
</P>
<P>
Nkomo said the search was being hampered by atrocious weather.
</P>
<P>
"Most regrettably, not much hope is left of finding anyone
alive," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The water conditions are treacherous and the water
temperature is about one degree Celsius. It is also snowing,"
the ambassador said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
