<HEADLINE> U.S. Ex-Im Bank Supports Oil Field Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Export-Import Bank
Monday announced that it would provide a loan guarantee to help
support 200 million U.S. dollars in exports of oil well services
to an oil field project off the shore of Angola in Sub-Sahara
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The bank used a secured offshore escrow account to assure
repayment of the exports.
</P>
<P>
The bank is guaranteeing an 87 million dollar loan by Societe
Generale of New York.
</P>
<P>
The Ex-Im Bank is a governmental agency that supports exports of
U.S. goods and services abroad. In fiscal year 1997, the bank
assisted 15 billion dollars in U.S. exports worldwide. The bank
has become active and open to consider business in 18 Sub-Saharan
African countries in the light of the government policy changes. In
fiscal year 1997, it supported 217 million dollars in U.S. exports
to Sub-Saharan Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
