<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Suicide Rate Hits Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The suicide rate in the Republic of
Ireland jumped to a record high in 1997 by increasing 14 percent
from 1996 to 433 cases, according to an official government report
released in Dublin Monday.
</P>
<P>
The government report said, male suicides outnumbered female by
355 to 78, and young or early middle-aged people formed the
largest group of suicides.
</P>
<P>
Health expert Feargal Bowers was quoted by Reuters as saying
that the figures were surprising in the context of Ireland's
booming economy.
</P>
<P>
Bowers noted that an increase in the divorce rate, and the
diminishing number of people attending church could have
contributed to the high suicide rate.
</P>
<P>
In view of the alarming figures, the country's opposition
parties called on the government to implement the findings of a
National Task Force set up in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The National Task Force recommended better training for doctors
and teachers to identify those at risk, and restrictions on the
availability of some painkiller pills.  
</P>
</TEXT>
