<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Probes Apartheid Regime's Chemical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) is investigating the apartheid
government's chemical and biological warfare program, which
included covert assassinations by poisoning and the manipulation
of fertility.
</P>
<P>
The hearing went ahead in public in Cape Town Monday after an
initial request by a government delegation for it to be held
behind closed-doors was rejected by the TRC in the interests of
transparency, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The TRC heard testimony from a former South African Defense
Force (SADF) Captain and bio-engineer who later formed his own
front company to design and develop a series of poison-bearing
weaponry, said SAPA.
</P>
<P>
Jan Lourens, a highly qualified scientist, said that he had
served in the South African Air Force and was later recruited by
the Special Operations Unit headed by Wouter Basson.
</P>
<P>
Basson is facing 10 criminal charges ranging from instigation
to murder and possession of huge quantities of drugs including
Ecstasy, to fraud of 50 million Rand (9.8 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Lourens said that he was initially involved in the supply of
low-key technical equipment for use by military doctors such as a
radio network, high performance motor vehicles and fold-up
rifles.
</P>
<P>
He said it was during this period in about 1985 that he became
aware of experimentation on animals such as chimpanzees and
baboons on a farm near the Roodeplaat Dam outside Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Lourens said later that he was involved in the testing of a
"new generation" tear gas called CR, as opposed to the old variety
called CS. Baboons were placed in clear plastic cages and
exposed to the tear gas.
</P>
<P>
Lourens told the commission that he later formed his own
company called Protechnic, which became involved in developing
weaponry for the SADF.
</P>
<P>
He had a close association with Basson, who he said had lines
of contact with the SADF's Surgeon-General and covert elements
within the SADF.
</P>
<P>
During this time he became aware of the SADF's biological
program, which was headed by Riana Boorman who had been working
on ways of affecting the virility and fertility of animals.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed she was aiming to ultimately use the
technology to manipulate the fertility of people in South Africa
on an ethnic basis.
</P>
<P>
Lourens said that he later met a weapons expert called Phil
Morgan who had developed mechanisms which could be used to propel
poisonous substances.
</P>
<P>
These included rings with secret compartment, walking sticks,
umbrellas, bicycle pumps and screw drivers.
</P>
<P>
He conceded later in the hearing that these were all designed
for use by assassins to kill people in a covert way.
</P>
<P>
Lourens told the hearing that he nearly became a victim of his
own gadget when he had to deliver a poison-bearing screw driver
to a man in England called Trevor.
</P>
<P>
Lourens said that he accidentally got a taste of the poison
while demonstrating the James Bond type gadget to Trevor.
</P>
<P>
He said he lost consciousness but was later told he was lucky
to have survived.
</P>
<P>
Lourens said that he also came across international arms
dealers interested in buying South African chemical weapons
technology. But, he said, nothing came of these deals as far as
he knew.
</P>
<P>
The hearings will continue Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
