<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Abacha to Be Buried Monday Night </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Late Nigerian Head of State General
Sani Abacha who died in the early hour of Monday will be buried
Monday night in northern Kano State where he was born, the
Nigerian TV Authority (NTA) said.
</P>
<P>
Footage of the NTA showed that the remains of Abacha, wrapped
in light blue cloth, was sent aboard a presidential plane and
left the Abuja airport for Kano at about 18:35 p.m. (local time).
</P>
<P>
The remains of Abacha left the presidential villa in an
ambulance at about 17:00 p.m. and was accompanied by his wife
Mariam Abacha, other family members, members of the Provisional
Ruling Council (PRC) and the Federal Executive Council.
</P>
<P>
The body of Abacha is expected to be buried late Monday night
according to Islamic customs, NTA said.
</P>
<P>
The death of Abacha was announced at about 17:00 p.m. by the
Chief of Defense Staff, Major-General Abdulsalam Abubakar, after
a meeting of the PRC, the country's highest decision-making body.
</P>
<P>
The official announcement said that Abacha died in sleep,
giving no reason of the death, but unconfirmed report quoted
Western Diplomats in Nigeria as saying that he died of heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
The state TV station said the PRC is expected to reconvene
Monday night at about 23:00 p.m., after the burial. It met from
12:00 p.m. to 17:00 p.m. to discuss the situation after Abacha's
death.
</P>
<P>
Abacha's death has been a kind of shock to Nigerians. He
reportedly met Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Sunday and held a
three-hour talk with him.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, 55, took over power from the interim government of
Chief Earnest Shonekan in November 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to the transition to civil rule program announced by
him in 1995, Abacha is expected to hand over power to an elected
civilian government in October this year.
</P>
<P>
In April, Nigeria's five political parties adopted Abacha as
their sole consensus candidate for the presidential election
scheduled to be held on August 1. But Abacha has been silent on
the issue until his death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
